// Pocket CoP — regulatory data
// cops: 42 CFR Part 482 CoP text
// igData: CMS SOM Interpretive Guidelines


// Each node: {type:'std',label,title} | {type:'p',label,text,indent} | {type:'text',text,indent}
const cops = [
// ── SUBPART A ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
{id:'482.1',citation:'§\u00a0482.1',title:'Basis and Scope',tags:['general'],subpart:'Subpart A \u2014 General Provisions',
intro:'Sets forth the conditions of participation (CoPs) that a hospital must meet in order to participate in the Medicare or Medicaid programs.',
body:[
{type:'p',label:'(a)',text:'Section 1861(e) of the Act establishes the requirements that a hospital must meet to participate in Medicare. Section 1902(a)(28) of the Act establishes requirements for Medicaid-participating hospitals. The Secretary may impose additional requirements if they are found necessary in the interest of the health and safety of individuals furnished services in hospitals.',indent:0},
{type:'p',label:'(b)',text:"Section 1861(f) of the Act provides that an institution participating as a psychiatric hospital must meet certain requirements imposed on hospitals under section 1861(e); must be primarily engaged in providing, by or under the supervision of a physician, psychiatric services for the diagnosis and treatment of mentally ill persons; must maintain clinical records and other records that the Secretary finds necessary; and must meet staffing requirements that the Secretary finds necessary to carry out an active program of treatment.",indent:0},
]},
// ── SUBPART B ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
{id:'482.11',citation:'§\u00a0482.11',title:'Compliance with Federal, State and Local Laws',tags:['general'],subpart:'Subpart B \u2014 Administration',
intro:'',
body:[
{type:'p',label:'(a)',text:'The hospital must be in compliance with applicable Federal laws related to the health and safety of patients.',indent:0},
{type:'p',label:'(b)',text:'The hospital must be\u2014',indent:0},
{type:'p',label:'(1)',text:'Licensed; or',indent:1},
{type:'p',label:'(2)',text:'Approved as meeting standards for licensing established by the agency of the State or locality responsible for licensing hospitals.',indent:1},
{type:'p',label:'(c)',text:'The hospital must assure that personnel are licensed or meet other applicable standards that are required by State or local laws.',indent:0},
]},
{id:'482.12',citation:'§\u00a0482.12',title:'Governing Body',tags:['general'],subpart:'Subpart B \u2014 Administration',
intro:'There must be an effective governing body that is legally responsible for the conduct of the hospital. If a hospital does not have an organized governing body, the persons legally responsible for the conduct of the hospital must carry out the functions specified in this part that pertain to the governing body.',
body:[
{type:'std',label:'(a)',title:'Standard: Medical staff.'},
{type:'text',text:'The governing body must:',indent:0},
{type:'p',label:'(1)',text:'Determine, in accordance with State law, which categories of practitioners are eligible candidates for appointment to the medical staff;',indent:1},
{type:'p',label:'(2)',text:'Appoint members of the medical staff after considering the recommendations of the existing members of the medical staff;',indent:1},
{type:'p',label:'(3)',text:'Assure that the medical staff has bylaws;',indent:1},
{type:'p',label:'(4)',text:'Approve medical staff bylaws and other medical staff rules and regulations;',indent:1},
{type:'p',label:'(5)',text:'Ensure that the medical staff is accountable to the governing body for the quality of care provided to patients;',indent:1},
{type:'p',label:'(6)',text:'Ensure the criteria for selection are individual character, competence, training, experience, and judgment; and',indent:1},
{type:'p',label:'(7)',text:'Ensure that under no circumstances is the accordance of staff membership or professional privileges in the hospital dependent solely upon certification, fellowship, or membership in a specialty body or society.',indent:1},
{type:'p',label:'(8)',text:"Ensure that, when telemedicine services are furnished to the hospital's patients through an agreement with a distant-site hospital, the agreement is written and specifies that it is the responsibility of the governing body of the distant-site hospital to meet the requirements in paragraphs (a)(1) through (a)(7) of this section.",indent:1},
{type:'p',label:'(9)',text:'Ensure that when telemedicine services are furnished through an agreement with a distant-site telemedicine entity, the written agreement specifies that the entity furnishes services in a manner that permits the hospital to comply with all applicable conditions of participation.',indent:1},
{type:'p',label:'(10)',text:"Consult directly with the individual assigned the responsibility for the organization and conduct of the hospital's medical staff, or his or her designee, at least periodically throughout the fiscal or calendar year on matters related to the quality of medical care provided to patients.",indent:1},
{type:'std',label:'(b)',title:'Standard: Chief executive officer.'},
{type:'text',text:'The governing body must appoint a chief executive officer who is responsible for managing the hospital.',indent:0},
{type:'std',label:'(c)',title:'Standard: Care of patients.'},
{type:'text',text:'In accordance with hospital policy, the governing body must ensure that:',indent:0},
{type:'p',label:'(1)',text:'Every Medicare patient is under the care of: (This provision is not to be construed to limit the authority of a doctor of medicine or osteopathy to delegate tasks to other qualified health care personnel to the extent recognized under State law.)',indent:1},
{type:'p',label:'(i)',text:'A doctor of medicine or osteopathy;',indent:2},
{type:'p',label:'(ii)',text:'A doctor of dental surgery or dental medicine who is legally authorized to practice dentistry by the State and who is acting within the scope of his or her license;',indent:2},
{type:'p',label:'(iii)',text:'A doctor of podiatric medicine, but only with respect to functions which he or she is legally authorized by the State to perform;',indent:2},
{type:'p',label:'(iv)',text:'A doctor of optometry who is legally authorized to practice optometry by the State in which he or she practices;',indent:2},
{type:'p',label:'(v)',text:'A chiropractor who is licensed by the State or legally authorized to perform the services of a chiropractor, but only with respect to treatment by means of manual manipulation of the spine to correct a subluxation demonstrated by x-ray to exist; and',indent:2},
{type:'p',label:'(vi)',text:'A clinical psychologist as defined in § 410.71, but only with respect to clinical psychologist services as defined in § 410.71 and only to the extent permitted by State law.',indent:2},
{type:'p',label:'(2)',text:'Patients are admitted to the hospital only on the recommendation of a licensed practitioner permitted by the State to admit patients to a hospital.',indent:1},
{type:'p',label:'(3)',text:'A doctor of medicine or osteopathy is on duty or on call at all times.',indent:1},
{type:'p',label:'(4)',text:'A doctor of medicine or osteopathy is responsible for the care of each Medicare patient with respect to any medical or psychiatric problem that\u2014',indent:1},
{type:'p',label:'(i)',text:'Is present on admission or develops during hospitalization; and',indent:2},
{type:'p',label:'(ii)',text:'Is not specifically within the scope of practice of a doctor of dental surgery, dental medicine, podiatric medicine, or optometry; a chiropractor; or clinical psychologist.',indent:2},
{type:'std',label:'(d)',title:'Standard: Institutional plan and budget.'},
{type:'text',text:'The institution must have an overall institutional plan that meets the following conditions:',indent:0},
{type:'p',label:'(1)',text:'The plan must include an annual operating budget prepared according to generally accepted accounting principles.',indent:1},
{type:'p',label:'(2)',text:'The budget must include all anticipated income and expenses.',indent:1},
{type:'p',label:'(3)',text:'The plan must provide for capital expenditures for at least a 3-year period.',indent:1},
{type:'p',label:'(4)',text:'The plan must include and identify in detail the objective of, and the anticipated sources of financing for, each anticipated capital expenditure in excess of $600,000 that relates to\u2014',indent:1},
{type:'p',label:'(i)',text:'Acquisition of land;',indent:2},
{type:'p',label:'(ii)',text:'Improvement of land, buildings, and equipment; or',indent:2},
{type:'p',label:'(iii)',text:'The replacement, modernization, and expansion of buildings and equipment.',indent:2},
{type:'p',label:'(5)',text:'The plan must be submitted for review to the planning agency designated in accordance with section 1122(b) of the Act.',indent:1},
{type:'p',label:'(6)',text:'The plan must be reviewed and updated annually.',indent:1},
{type:'p',label:'(7)',text:'The plan must be prepared\u2014',indent:1},
{type:'p',label:'(i)',text:'Under the direction of the governing body; and',indent:2},
{type:'p',label:'(ii)',text:'By a committee consisting of representatives of the governing body, the administrative staff, and the medical staff of the institution.',indent:2},
{type:'std',label:'(e)',title:'Standard: Contracted services.'},
{type:'text',text:"The governing body must be responsible for services furnished in the hospital whether or not they are furnished under contracts. The governing body must ensure that a contractor furnishes services that permit the hospital to comply with all applicable conditions of participation.",indent:0},
{type:'p',label:'(1)',text:'The governing body must ensure that the services performed under a contract are provided in a safe and effective manner.',indent:1},
{type:'p',label:'(2)',text:'The hospital must maintain a list of all contracted services, including the scope and nature of the services provided.',indent:1},
{type:'std',label:'(f)',title:'Standard: Emergency services.'},
{type:'p',label:'(1)',text:'If emergency services are provided at the hospital, the hospital must comply with the requirements of § 482.55.',indent:1},
{type:'p',label:'(2)',text:'If emergency services are not provided at the hospital, the governing body must assure that the medical staff has written policies and procedures for appraisal of emergencies, initial treatment, and referral when appropriate.',indent:1},
{type:'p',label:'(3)',text:'If emergency services are provided at the hospital but not at one or more off-campus departments, the governing body must assure that the medical staff has written policies and procedures for those off-campus departments for appraisal of emergencies and referral when appropriate.',indent:1},
]},
{id:'482.13',citation:'§\u00a0482.13',title:"Patient's Rights",tags:['general'],subpart:'Subpart B \u2014 Administration',
intro:"A hospital must protect and promote each patient's rights.",
body:[
{type:'std',label:'(a)',title:'Standard: Notice of rights.'},
{type:'p',label:'(1)',text:"A hospital must inform each patient, or when appropriate, the patient's representative (as allowed under State law), of the patient's rights, in advance of furnishing or discontinuing patient care whenever possible.",indent:1},
{type:'p',label:'(2)',text:"The hospital must establish a process for prompt resolution of patient grievances and must inform each patient whom to contact to file a grievance. At a minimum:",indent:1},
{type:'p',label:'(i)',text:"The hospital must establish a clearly explained procedure for the submission of a patient's written or verbal grievance to the hospital.",indent:2},
{type:'p',label:'(ii)',text:'The grievance process must specify time frames for review of the grievance and the provision of a response.',indent:2},
{type:'p',label:'(iii)',text:"In its resolution of the grievance, the hospital must provide the patient with written notice of its decision that contains the name of the hospital contact person, the steps taken on behalf of the patient to investigate the grievance, the results of the grievance process, and the date of completion.",indent:2},
{type:'std',label:'(b)',title:'Standard: Exercise of rights.'},
{type:'p',label:'(1)',text:"The patient has the right to participate in the development and implementation of his or her plan of care.",indent:1},
{type:'p',label:'(2)',text:"The patient or his or her representative (as allowed under State law) has the right to make informed decisions regarding his or her care. The patient's rights include being informed of his or her health status, being involved in care planning and treatment, and being able to request or refuse treatment. This right must not be construed as a mechanism to demand the provision of treatment or services deemed medically unnecessary or inappropriate.",indent:1},
{type:'p',label:'(3)',text:"The patient has the right to formulate advance directives and to have hospital staff and practitioners who provide care in the hospital comply with these directives, in accordance with § 489.100, § 489.102, and § 489.104 of this part.",indent:1},
{type:'p',label:'(4)',text:"The patient has the right to have a family member or representative of his or her choice and his or her own physician notified promptly of his or her admission to the hospital.",indent:1},
{type:'std',label:'(c)',title:'Standard: Privacy and safety.'},
{type:'p',label:'(1)',text:"The patient has the right to personal privacy.",indent:1},
{type:'p',label:'(2)',text:"The patient has the right to receive care in a safe setting.",indent:1},
{type:'p',label:'(3)',text:"The patient has the right to be free from all forms of abuse or harassment.",indent:1},
{type:'std',label:'(d)',title:'Standard: Confidentiality of patient records.'},
{type:'p',label:'(1)',text:"The patient has the right to the confidentiality of his or her clinical records.",indent:1},
{type:'p',label:'(2)',text:"The patient has the right to access their medical records, including current medical records, upon an oral or written request, in the form and format requested by the individual, if it is readily producible in such form and format; or, if not, in a readable hard copy form or such other form and format as agreed to by the facility and the individual, and within a reasonable time frame.",indent:1},
{type:'std',label:'(e)',title:'Standard: Restraint or seclusion.'},
{type:'text',text:"All patients have the right to be free from physical or mental abuse, and corporal punishment. All patients have the right to be free from restraint or seclusion, of any form, imposed as a means of coercion, discipline, convenience, or retaliation by staff. Restraint or seclusion may only be imposed to ensure the immediate physical safety of the patient, a staff member, or others and must be discontinued at the earliest possible time.",indent:0},
{type:'p',label:'(1)',text:'Definitions.',indent:1},
{type:'p',label:'(i)',text:"A restraint is\u2014",indent:2},
{type:'p',label:'(A)',text:"Any manual method, physical or mechanical device, material, or equipment that immobilizes or reduces the ability of a patient to move his or her arms, legs, body, or head freely; or",indent:3},
{type:'p',label:'(B)',text:"A drug or medication when it is used as a restriction to manage the patient's behavior or restrict the patient's freedom of movement and is not a standard treatment or dosage for the patient's condition.",indent:3},
{type:'p',label:'(C)',text:"A restraint does not include devices such as orthopedically prescribed devices, surgical dressings or bandages, protective helmets, or other methods that involve the physical holding of a patient for the purpose of conducting routine physical examinations or tests, or to protect the patient from falling out of bed, or to permit the patient to participate in activities without the risk of physical harm.",indent:3},
{type:'p',label:'(ii)',text:"Seclusion is the involuntary confinement of a patient alone in a room or area from which the patient is physically prevented from leaving. Seclusion may only be used for the management of violent or self-destructive behavior.",indent:2},
{type:'p',label:'(2)',text:"Restraint or seclusion may only be used when less restrictive interventions have been determined to be ineffective to protect the patient, a staff member, or others from harm.",indent:1},
{type:'p',label:'(3)',text:"The type or technique of restraint or seclusion used must be the least restrictive intervention that will be effective to protect the patient, a staff member, or others from harm.",indent:1},
{type:'p',label:'(4)',text:"The use of restraint or seclusion must be\u2014",indent:1},
{type:'p',label:'(i)',text:"In accordance with a written modification to the patient's plan of care; and",indent:2},
{type:'p',label:'(ii)',text:"Implemented in accordance with safe and appropriate restraint and seclusion techniques as determined by hospital policy in accordance with State law.",indent:2},
{type:'p',label:'(5)',text:"The use of restraint or seclusion must be in accordance with the order of a physician or other licensed practitioner who is responsible for the care of the patient and authorized to order restraint or seclusion by hospital policy in accordance with State law.",indent:1},
{type:'p',label:'(6)',text:"Orders for the use of restraint or seclusion must never be written as a standing order or on an as needed basis (PRN).",indent:1},
{type:'p',label:'(7)',text:"The attending physician must be consulted as soon as possible if the attending physician did not order the restraint or seclusion.",indent:1},
{type:'p',label:'(8)',text:"Unless superseded by State law that is more restrictive\u2014",indent:1},
{type:'p',label:'(i)',text:"Each order for restraint or seclusion used for the management of violent or self-destructive behavior may only be renewed in accordance with the following limits for up to a total of 24 hours:",indent:2},
{type:'p',label:'(A)',text:"4 hours for adults 18 years of age or older;",indent:3},
{type:'p',label:'(B)',text:"2 hours for children and adolescents 9 to 17 years of age; or",indent:3},
{type:'p',label:'(C)',text:"1 hour for children under 9 years of age; and",indent:3},
{type:'p',label:'(ii)',text:"After 24 hours, before writing a new order for the use of restraint or seclusion, a physician or other licensed practitioner must see and assess the patient.",indent:2},
{type:'p',label:'(iii)',text:"Each order for restraint used to ensure the physical safety of the non-violent or non-self-destructive patient may be renewed as authorized by hospital policy.",indent:2},
{type:'p',label:'(9)',text:"Restraint or seclusion must be discontinued at the earliest possible time, regardless of the length of time identified in the order.",indent:1},
{type:'p',label:'(10)',text:"The condition of the patient who is restrained or secluded must be monitored by a physician, other licensed practitioner, or trained staff at an interval determined by hospital policy.",indent:1},
{type:'p',label:'(11)',text:"Physician and other licensed practitioner training requirements must be specified in hospital policy. At a minimum, physicians and other licensed practitioners authorized to order restraint or seclusion must have a working knowledge of hospital policy regarding the use of restraint or seclusion.",indent:1},
{type:'p',label:'(12)',text:"When restraint or seclusion is used for the management of violent or self-destructive behavior that jeopardizes the immediate physical safety of the patient, a staff member, or others, the patient must be seen face-to-face within 1 hour after the initiation of the intervention\u2014",indent:1},
{type:'p',label:'(i)',text:"By a\u2014",indent:2},
{type:'p',label:'(A)',text:"Physician or other licensed practitioner; or",indent:3},
{type:'p',label:'(B)',text:"Registered nurse who has been trained in accordance with the requirements of paragraph (f) of this section.",indent:3},
{type:'p',label:'(ii)',text:"To evaluate\u2014",indent:2},
{type:'p',label:'(A)',text:"The patient's immediate situation;",indent:3},
{type:'p',label:'(B)',text:"The patient's reaction to the intervention;",indent:3},
{type:'p',label:'(C)',text:"The patient's medical and behavioral condition; and",indent:3},
{type:'p',label:'(D)',text:"The need to continue or terminate the restraint or seclusion.",indent:3},
{type:'p',label:'(13)',text:"States are free to have requirements by statute or regulation that are more restrictive than those contained in paragraph (e)(12)(i) of this section.",indent:1},
{type:'p',label:'(14)',text:"If the face-to-face evaluation specified in paragraph (e)(12) is conducted by a trained registered nurse, the trained registered nurse must consult the attending physician or other licensed practitioner who is responsible for the care of the patient as soon as possible after the completion of the 1-hour face-to-face evaluation.",indent:1},
{type:'p',label:'(15)',text:"All requirements specified under this paragraph are applicable to the simultaneous use of restraint and seclusion. Simultaneous restraint and seclusion use is only permitted if the patient is continually monitored\u2014",indent:1},
{type:'p',label:'(i)',text:"Face-to-face by an assigned, trained staff member; or",indent:2},
{type:'p',label:'(ii)',text:"By trained staff using both video and audio equipment. This monitoring must be in close proximity to the patient.",indent:2},
{type:'p',label:'(16)',text:"When restraint or seclusion is used, there must be documentation in the patient's medical record of the following:",indent:1},
{type:'p',label:'(i)',text:"The 1-hour face-to-face medical and behavioral evaluation if restraint or seclusion is used to manage violent or self-destructive behavior;",indent:2},
{type:'p',label:'(ii)',text:"A description of the patient's behavior and the intervention used;",indent:2},
{type:'p',label:'(iii)',text:"Alternatives or other less restrictive interventions attempted (as applicable);",indent:2},
{type:'p',label:'(iv)',text:"The patient's condition or symptom(s) that warranted the use of the restraint or seclusion; and",indent:2},
{type:'p',label:'(v)',text:"The patient's response to the intervention(s) used, including the rationale for continued use of the intervention.",indent:2},
{type:'std',label:'(f)',title:'Standard: Restraint or seclusion: Staff training requirements.'},
{type:'text',text:"The patient has the right to safe implementation of restraint or seclusion by trained staff.",indent:0},
{type:'p',label:'(1)',text:"Training intervals. Staff must be trained and able to demonstrate competency in the application of restraints, implementation of seclusion, monitoring, assessment, and providing care for a patient in restraint or seclusion\u2014",indent:1},
{type:'p',label:'(i)',text:"Before performing any of the actions specified in this paragraph;",indent:2},
{type:'p',label:'(ii)',text:"As part of orientation; and",indent:2},
{type:'p',label:'(iii)',text:"Subsequently on a periodic basis consistent with hospital policy.",indent:2},
{type:'p',label:'(2)',text:"Training content. The hospital must require appropriate staff to have education, training, and demonstrated knowledge based on the specific needs of the patient population in at least the following:",indent:1},
{type:'p',label:'(i)',text:"Techniques to identify staff and patient behaviors, events, and environmental factors that may trigger circumstances that require the use of a restraint or seclusion.",indent:2},
{type:'p',label:'(ii)',text:"The use of nonphysical intervention skills.",indent:2},
{type:'p',label:'(iii)',text:"Choosing the least restrictive intervention based on an individualized assessment of the patient's medical, or behavioral status or condition.",indent:2},
{type:'p',label:'(iv)',text:"The safe application and use of all types of restraint or seclusion used in the hospital, including training in how to recognize and respond to signs of physical and psychological distress (for example, positional asphyxia).",indent:2},
{type:'p',label:'(v)',text:"Clinical identification of specific behavioral changes that indicate that restraint or seclusion is no longer necessary.",indent:2},
{type:'p',label:'(vi)',text:"Monitoring the physical and psychological well-being of the patient who is restrained or secluded, including but not limited to, respiratory and circulatory status, skin integrity, vital signs, and any special requirements associated with the 1-hour face-to-face evaluation.",indent:2},
{type:'p',label:'(vii)',text:"The use of first aid techniques and certification in the use of cardiopulmonary resuscitation, including required periodic recertification.",indent:2},
{type:'p',label:'(3)',text:"Trainer requirements. Individuals providing staff training must be qualified as evidenced by education, training, and experience in techniques used to address patients' behaviors.",indent:1},
{type:'p',label:'(4)',text:"Training documentation. The hospital must document in the staff personnel records that the training and demonstration of competency were successfully completed.",indent:1},
{type:'std',label:'(g)',title:'Standard: Death reporting requirements.'},
{type:'text',text:'Hospitals must report deaths associated with the use of seclusion or restraint.',indent:0},
{type:'p',label:'(1)',text:"With the exception of deaths described under paragraph (g)(2) of this section, the hospital must report the following information to CMS no later than the close of business on the next business day following knowledge of the patient's death:",indent:1},
{type:'p',label:'(i)',text:"Each death that occurs while a patient is in restraint or seclusion.",indent:2},
{type:'p',label:'(ii)',text:"Each death that occurs within 24 hours after the patient has been removed from restraint or seclusion.",indent:2},
{type:'p',label:'(iii)',text:"Each death known to the hospital that occurs within 1 week after restraint or seclusion where it is reasonable to assume that use of restraint or placement in seclusion contributed directly or indirectly to a patient's death.",indent:2},
{type:'p',label:'(2)',text:"When no seclusion has been used and when the only restraints used on the patient are those applied exclusively to the patient's wrist(s) and composed solely of soft, non-rigid, cloth-like materials, the hospital staff must record in an internal log the following information:",indent:1},
{type:'p',label:'(i)',text:"Any death that occurs while a patient is in such restraints.",indent:2},
{type:'p',label:'(ii)',text:"Any death that occurs within 24 hours after a patient has been removed from such restraints.",indent:2},
{type:'p',label:'(3)',text:"The staff must document in the patient's medical record the date and time the death was:",indent:1},
{type:'p',label:'(i)',text:"Reported to CMS for deaths described in paragraph (g)(1) of this section; or",indent:2},
{type:'p',label:'(ii)',text:"Recorded in the internal log or other system for deaths described in paragraph (g)(2) of this section.",indent:2},
{type:'std',label:'(h)',title:'Standard: Patient visitation rights.'},
{type:'text',text:"A hospital must have written policies and procedures regarding the visitation rights of patients, including any clinically necessary or reasonable restriction or limitation that the hospital may need to place on such rights and the reasons for the clinical restriction or limitation. A hospital must meet the following requirements:",indent:0},
{type:'p',label:'(1)',text:"Inform each patient (or support person, where appropriate) of his or her visitation rights, including any clinical restriction or limitation on such rights, when he or she is informed of his or her other rights under this section.",indent:1},
{type:'p',label:'(2)',text:"Inform each patient (or support person, where appropriate) of the right, subject to his or her consent, to receive the visitors whom he or she designates, including, but not limited to, a spouse, a domestic partner (including a same-sex domestic partner), another family member, or a friend, and his or her right to withdraw or deny such consent at any time.",indent:1},
{type:'p',label:'(3)',text:"Not restrict, limit, or otherwise deny visitation privileges on the basis of race, color, national origin, religion, sex, gender identity, sexual orientation, or disability.",indent:1},
{type:'p',label:'(4)',text:"Ensure that all visitors enjoy full and equal visitation privileges consistent with patient preferences.",indent:1},
]},
{id:'482.15',citation:'§\u00a0482.15',title:'Emergency Preparedness',tags:['general'],subpart:'Subpart B \u2014 Administration',
intro:'The hospital must comply with all applicable Federal, State, and local emergency preparedness requirements. The hospital must develop and maintain a comprehensive emergency preparedness program, utilizing an all-hazards approach.',
body:[
{type:'std',label:'(a)',title:'Standard: Emergency plan.'},
{type:'text',text:'The hospital must develop and maintain an emergency preparedness plan that must be reviewed and updated at least every 2 years. The plan must:',indent:0},
{type:'p',label:'(1)',text:'Be based on and include a documented, facility-based and community-based risk assessment, utilizing an all-hazards approach.',indent:1},
{type:'p',label:'(2)',text:'Include strategies for addressing emergency events identified by the risk assessment.',indent:1},
{type:'p',label:'(3)',text:'Address patient population, including persons at-risk; the type of services the hospital has the ability to provide in an emergency; and continuity of operations, including delegations of authority and succession plans.',indent:1},
{type:'p',label:'(4)',text:"Include a process for cooperation and collaboration with local, tribal, regional, State, and Federal emergency preparedness officials' efforts to maintain an integrated response during a disaster or emergency situation.",indent:1},
{type:'std',label:'(b)',title:'Standard: Policies and procedures.'},
{type:'text',text:'The hospital must develop and implement emergency preparedness policies and procedures, reviewed and updated at least every 2 years. At a minimum, the policies and procedures must address the following:',indent:0},
{type:'p',label:'(1)',text:'The provision of subsistence needs for staff and patients, whether they evacuate or shelter in place, including, but not limited to the following:',indent:1},
{type:'p',label:'(i)',text:'Food, water, medical, and pharmaceutical supplies.',indent:2},
{type:'p',label:'(ii)',text:'Alternate sources of energy to maintain the following:',indent:2},
{type:'p',label:'(A)',text:'Temperatures to protect patient health and safety and for the safe and sanitary storage of provisions.',indent:3},
{type:'p',label:'(B)',text:'Emergency lighting.',indent:3},
{type:'p',label:'(C)',text:'Fire detection, extinguishing, and alarm systems.',indent:3},
{type:'p',label:'(D)',text:'Sewage and waste disposal.',indent:3},
{type:'p',label:'(2)',text:"A system to track the location of on-duty staff and sheltered patients in the hospital's care during an emergency.",indent:1},
{type:'p',label:'(3)',text:"Safe evacuation from the hospital, including consideration of care and treatment needs of evacuees; staff responsibilities; transportation; identification of evacuation location(s); and primary and alternate means of communication with external sources of assistance.",indent:1},
{type:'p',label:'(4)',text:'A means to shelter in place for patients, staff, and volunteers who remain in the facility.',indent:1},
{type:'p',label:'(5)',text:'A system of medical documentation that preserves patient information, protects confidentiality of patient information, and secures and maintains the availability of records.',indent:1},
{type:'std',label:'(c)',title:'Standard: Communication plan.'},
{type:'text',text:'The hospital must develop and maintain an emergency preparedness communication plan that complies with Federal, State, and local laws and must include at a minimum:',indent:0},
{type:'p',label:'(1)',text:"Names and contact information for the following: (i) Staff; (ii) Entities providing services under arrangement; (iii) Patients' physicians; (iv) Other hospitals and CAHs; (v) Volunteers.",indent:1},
{type:'p',label:'(2)',text:'Primary and alternate means for communicating with the following:',indent:1},
{type:'p',label:'(i)',text:'Staff of the hospital;',indent:2},
{type:'p',label:'(ii)',text:'Federal, State, tribal, regional, and local emergency management agencies;',indent:2},
{type:'p',label:'(iii)',text:'The medical staff of the hospital;',indent:2},
{type:'p',label:'(iv)',text:'Other hospitals; and',indent:2},
{type:'p',label:'(v)',text:'Volunteers.',indent:2},
{type:'std',label:'(d)',title:'Standard: Training and testing.'},
{type:'text',text:'The hospital must develop and maintain an emergency preparedness training and testing program, reviewed and updated at least every 2 years. The program must:',indent:0},
{type:'p',label:'(1)',text:'Provide initial training in emergency preparedness policies and procedures to all new and existing staff, individuals providing services under arrangement, and volunteers.',indent:1},
{type:'p',label:'(2)',text:'Provide emergency preparedness training at least every 2 years.',indent:1},
{type:'p',label:'(3)',text:'Conduct exercises to test the emergency plan, including at least one full-scale exercise annually, and at least one additional exercise annually that may be a tabletop exercise or drill.',indent:1},
]},
// ── SUBPART C ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
{id:'482.21',citation:'§\u00a0482.21',title:'Quality Assessment and Performance Improvement (QAPI)',tags:['general'],subpart:'Subpart C \u2014 Basic Hospital Functions',
intro:"The hospital must develop, implement, and maintain an effective, ongoing, hospital-wide, data-driven quality assessment and performance improvement program. The hospital's governing body must ensure that the program reflects the complexity of the hospital's organization and services; involves all hospital departments and services (including those services furnished under contract or arrangement); and focuses on indicators related to improved health outcomes and the prevention and reduction of medical errors. The hospital must maintain and demonstrate evidence of its QAPI program for review by CMS.",
body:[
{type:'std',label:'(a)',title:'Standard: Program scope.'},
{type:'p',label:'(1)',text:'The program must include, but not be limited to, an ongoing program that shows measurable improvement in indicators for which there is evidence that it will improve health outcomes and identify and reduce medical errors.',indent:1},
{type:'p',label:'(2)',text:'The hospital must measure, analyze, and track quality indicators, including adverse patient events, and other aspects of performance that assess processes of care, hospital service and operations.',indent:1},
{type:'std',label:'(b)',title:'Standard: Program data.'},
{type:'p',label:'(1)',text:'The program must incorporate quality indicator data including patient care data, and other relevant data such as data submitted to or received from Medicare quality reporting and quality performance programs, including but not limited to data related to hospital readmissions and hospital-acquired conditions.',indent:1},
{type:'p',label:'(2)',text:'The hospital must use the data collected to\u2014',indent:1},
{type:'p',label:'(i)',text:'Monitor the effectiveness and safety of services and quality of care; and',indent:2},
{type:'p',label:'(ii)',text:'Identify opportunities for improvement and changes that will lead to improvement.',indent:2},
{type:'p',label:'(3)',text:"The frequency and detail of data collection must be specified by the hospital's governing body.",indent:1},
{type:'std',label:'(c)',title:'Standard: Program activities.'},
{type:'p',label:'(1)',text:'The hospital must set priorities for its performance improvement activities that\u2014',indent:1},
{type:'p',label:'(i)',text:'Focus on high-risk, high-volume, or problem-prone areas;',indent:2},
{type:'p',label:'(ii)',text:'Consider the incidence, prevalence, and severity of problems in those areas; and',indent:2},
{type:'p',label:'(iii)',text:'Affect health outcomes, patient safety, and quality of care.',indent:2},
{type:'p',label:'(2)',text:'Performance improvement activities must track medical errors and adverse patient events, analyze their causes, and implement preventive actions and mechanisms that include feedback and learning throughout the hospital.',indent:1},
{type:'p',label:'(3)',text:'The hospital must take actions aimed at performance improvement and, after implementing those actions, the hospital must measure its success and track performance to ensure that improvements are sustained.',indent:1},
{type:'std',label:'(d)',title:'Standard: Performance improvement projects.'},
{type:'p',label:'(1)',text:"The number and scope of distinct improvement projects conducted annually must be proportional to the scope and complexity of the hospital's services and operations.",indent:1},
{type:'p',label:'(2)',text:'A hospital may, as one of its projects, develop and implement an information technology system explicitly designed to improve patient safety and quality of care.',indent:1},
{type:'p',label:'(3)',text:'The hospital must document what quality improvement projects are being conducted, the reasons for conducting these projects, and the measurable progress achieved on these projects.',indent:1},
{type:'std',label:'(f)',title:'Standard: Executive responsibilities.'},
{type:'text',text:"The hospital's governing body, medical staff, and administrative officials are responsible and accountable for ensuring the following:",indent:0},
{type:'p',label:'(1)',text:'That an ongoing program for quality improvement and patient safety, including the reduction of medical errors, is defined, implemented, and maintained.',indent:1},
{type:'p',label:'(2)',text:'That the hospital-wide QAPI efforts address priorities for improved quality of care and patient safety; and that all improvement actions are evaluated.',indent:1},
{type:'p',label:'(3)',text:'That clear expectations for safety are established.',indent:1},
{type:'p',label:'(4)',text:"That adequate resources are allocated for measuring, assessing, improving, and sustaining the hospital's performance and reducing risk to patients.",indent:1},
{type:'p',label:'(5)',text:'That the determination of the number of distinct improvement projects is conducted annually.',indent:1},
]},
{id:'482.22',citation:'§\u00a0482.22',title:'Medical Staff',tags:['general'],subpart:'Subpart C \u2014 Basic Hospital Functions',
intro:"The hospital must have an organized medical staff that operates under bylaws approved by the governing body, and which is responsible for the quality of medical care provided to patients by the hospital.",
body:[
{type:'std',label:'(a)',title:'Standard: Eligibility and process for appointment to medical staff.'},
{type:'text',text:'The medical staff must be composed of doctors of medicine or osteopathy. In accordance with State law, including scope-of-practice laws, the medical staff may also include other categories of physicians and non-physician practitioners who are determined to be eligible for appointment by the governing body.',indent:0},
{type:'p',label:'(1)',text:'The medical staff must periodically conduct appraisals of its members.',indent:1},
{type:'p',label:'(2)',text:'The medical staff must examine the credentials of all eligible candidates for medical staff membership and make recommendations to the governing body on the appointment of these candidates in accordance with State law, including scope-of-practice laws, and the medical staff bylaws, rules, and regulations.',indent:1},
{type:'p',label:'(3)',text:"When telemedicine services are furnished through an agreement with a distant-site hospital, the governing body of the receiving hospital may choose, in lieu of the requirements in paragraphs (a)(1) and (a)(2), to have its medical staff rely upon the credentialing and privileging decisions made by the distant-site hospital, if all of the following provisions are met:",indent:1},
{type:'p',label:'(i)',text:"The distant-site hospital providing the telemedicine services is a Medicare-participating hospital.",indent:2},
{type:'p',label:'(ii)',text:"The individual distant-site physician or practitioner is privileged at the distant-site hospital, which provides the receiving hospital with a current list of the distant-site physician's or practitioner's privileges.",indent:2},
{type:'p',label:'(iii)',text:"The individual distant-site physician or practitioner holds a license issued or recognized by the State in which the receiving hospital is located.",indent:2},
{type:'p',label:'(iv)',text:"The receiving hospital has evidence of an internal review of the distant-site physician's or practitioner's performance of these privileges and sends the distant-site hospital such performance information for use in periodic appraisal.",indent:2},
{type:'p',label:'(4)',text:'When telemedicine services are furnished through an agreement with a distant-site telemedicine entity, similar provisions apply as specified in this paragraph.',indent:1},
{type:'std',label:'(b)',title:'Standard: Medical staff organization and accountability.'},
{type:'text',text:'The medical staff must be well organized and accountable to the governing body for the quality of the medical care provided to patients.',indent:0},
{type:'p',label:'(1)',text:'The medical staff must be organized in a manner approved by the governing body.',indent:1},
{type:'p',label:'(2)',text:'If the medical staff has an executive committee, a majority of the members of the committee must be doctors of medicine or osteopathy.',indent:1},
{type:'p',label:'(3)',text:'The responsibility for organization and conduct of the medical staff must be assigned only to one of the following:',indent:1},
{type:'p',label:'(i)',text:'An individual doctor of medicine or osteopathy.',indent:2},
{type:'p',label:'(ii)',text:'A doctor of dental surgery or dental medicine, when permitted by State law of the State in which the hospital is located.',indent:2},
{type:'p',label:'(iii)',text:'A doctor of podiatric medicine, when permitted by State law of the State in which the hospital is located.',indent:2},
{type:'std',label:'(c)',title:'Standard: Medical staff bylaws.'},
{type:'text',text:'The medical staff must adopt and enforce bylaws to carry out its responsibilities. The bylaws must:',indent:0},
{type:'p',label:'(1)',text:'Be approved by the governing body.',indent:1},
{type:'p',label:'(2)',text:'Include a statement of the duties and privileges of each category of medical staff (e.g., active, courtesy, etc.).',indent:1},
{type:'p',label:'(3)',text:'Describe the organization of the medical staff.',indent:1},
{type:'p',label:'(4)',text:'Describe the qualifications to be met by a candidate in order for the medical staff to recommend appointment by the governing body.',indent:1},
{type:'p',label:'(5)',text:'Include a requirement that\u2014',indent:1},
{type:'p',label:'(i)',text:"A medical history and physical examination be completed and documented for each patient no more than 30 days before or 24 hours after admission or registration, but prior to surgery or a procedure requiring anesthesia services. The medical history and physical examination must be completed and documented by a physician (as defined in section 1861(r) of the Act), an oral and maxillofacial surgeon, or other qualified licensed individual in accordance with State law and hospital policy.",indent:2},
{type:'p',label:'(ii)',text:"An updated examination of the patient, including any changes in the patient's condition, be completed and documented within 24 hours after admission or registration, but prior to surgery or a procedure requiring anesthesia services, when the medical history and physical examination are completed within 30 days before admission or registration.",indent:2},
{type:'p',label:'(iii)',text:"An assessment of the patient (in lieu of the requirements of paragraphs (c)(5)(i) and (ii)) be completed and documented after registration, but prior to surgery or a procedure requiring anesthesia services, when the patient is receiving specific outpatient surgical or procedural services and when the medical staff has chosen to develop and maintain a policy identifying specific patients as not requiring a comprehensive H&P prior to specific outpatient surgical or procedural services.",indent:2},
{type:'p',label:'(6)',text:'Include criteria for determining the privileges to be granted to individual practitioners and a procedure for applying the criteria to individuals requesting privileges.',indent:1},
]},
{id:'482.23',citation:'§\u00a0482.23',title:'Nursing Services',tags:['general'],subpart:'Subpart C \u2014 Basic Hospital Functions',
intro:'The hospital must have an organized nursing service that provides 24-hour nursing services. The nursing services must be furnished or supervised by a registered nurse.',
body:[
{type:'std',label:'(a)',title:'Standard: Organization.'},
{type:'text',text:"The hospital must have a well-organized service with a plan of administrative authority and delineation of responsibilities for patient care. The director of the nursing service must be a licensed registered nurse. He or she is responsible for the operation of the service, including determining the types and numbers of nursing personnel and staff necessary to provide nursing care for all areas of the hospital.",indent:0},
{type:'std',label:'(b)',title:'Standard: Staffing and delivery of care.'},
{type:'text',text:'The nursing service must have adequate numbers of licensed registered nurses, licensed practical (vocational) nurses, and other personnel to provide nursing care to all patients as needed. There must be supervisory and staff personnel for each department or nursing unit to ensure, when needed, the immediate availability of a registered nurse for the care of any patient.',indent:0},
{type:'p',label:'(1)',text:'The hospital must provide 24-hour nursing services furnished or supervised by a registered nurse, and have a licensed practical nurse or registered nurse on duty at all times, except for rural hospitals that have in effect a 24-hour nursing waiver granted under § 488.54(c).',indent:1},
{type:'p',label:'(2)',text:'The nursing service must have a procedure to ensure that hospital nursing personnel for whom licensure is required have valid and current licensure.',indent:1},
{type:'p',label:'(3)',text:"A registered nurse must supervise and evaluate the nursing care for each patient.",indent:1},
{type:'p',label:'(4)',text:"The hospital must ensure that the nursing staff develops and keeps current a nursing care plan for each patient that reflects the patient's goals and the nursing care to be provided to meet the patient's needs. The nursing care plan may be part of an interdisciplinary care plan.",indent:1},
{type:'p',label:'(5)',text:"A registered nurse must assign the nursing care of each patient to other nursing personnel in accordance with the patient's needs and the specialized qualifications and competence of the nursing staff available.",indent:1},
{type:'p',label:'(6)',text:"All licensed nurses who provide services in the hospital must adhere to the policies and procedures of the hospital.",indent:1},
{type:'p',label:'(7)',text:"The hospital must have policies and procedures in place establishing which outpatient departments, if any, are not required under hospital policy to have a registered nurse present. The policies and procedures must:",indent:1},
{type:'p',label:'(i)',text:"Establish the criteria such outpatient departments must meet, taking into account the types of services delivered, the general level of acuity of patients served by the department, and the established standards of practice for the services delivered;",indent:2},
{type:'p',label:'(ii)',text:'Establish alternative staffing plans;',indent:2},
{type:'p',label:'(iii)',text:'Be approved by the director of nursing;',indent:2},
{type:'p',label:'(iv)',text:'Be reviewed at least once every 3 years.',indent:2},
{type:'std',label:'(c)',title:'Standard: Preparation and administration of drugs.'},
{type:'p',label:'(1)',text:"Drugs and biologicals must be prepared and administered in accordance with Federal and State laws, the orders of the practitioner or practitioners responsible for the patient's care, and accepted standards of practice.",indent:1},
{type:'p',label:'(i)',text:"Drugs and biologicals may be prepared and administered on the orders of other practitioners not specified under § 482.12(c) only if such practitioners are acting in accordance with State law, including scope-of-practice laws, hospital policies, and medical staff bylaws, rules, and regulations.",indent:2},
{type:'p',label:'(ii)',text:"Drugs and biologicals may be prepared and administered on the orders contained within pre-printed and electronic standing orders, order sets, and protocols for patient orders only if such orders meet the requirements of § 482.24(c)(3).",indent:2},
{type:'p',label:'(2)',text:'All drugs and biologicals must be administered by, or under supervision of, nursing or other personnel in accordance with Federal and State laws and regulations, including applicable licensing requirements, and in accordance with the approved medical staff policies and procedures.',indent:1},
{type:'p',label:'(3)',text:'With the exception of influenza and pneumococcal vaccines, which may be administered per physician-approved hospital policy after an assessment of contraindications, orders for drugs and biologicals must be documented and signed by a practitioner authorized to write orders in accordance with State law and hospital policy.',indent:1},
{type:'p',label:'(i)',text:'If verbal orders are used, they are to be used infrequently.',indent:2},
{type:'p',label:'(ii)',text:'When verbal orders are used, they must only be accepted by persons who are authorized to do so by hospital policy and procedures consistent with Federal and State law.',indent:2},
{type:'p',label:'(iii)',text:"Orders for drugs and biologicals may be documented and signed by other practitioners only if such practitioners are acting in accordance with State law, including scope-of-practice laws, hospital policies, and medical staff bylaws, rules, and regulations.",indent:2},
{type:'p',label:'(4)',text:'Blood transfusions and intravenous medications must be administered in accordance with State law and approved medical staff policies and procedures.',indent:1},
{type:'p',label:'(5)',text:'There must be a hospital procedure for reporting transfusion reactions, adverse drug reactions, and errors in administration of drugs.',indent:1},
{type:'p',label:'(6)',text:"The hospital may allow a patient (or his or her caregiver/support person where appropriate) to self-administer both hospital-issued medications and the patient's own medications brought into the hospital, as defined and specified in the hospital's policies and procedures.",indent:1},
]},
{id:'482.24',citation:'§\u00a0482.24',title:'Medical Record Services',tags:['general'],subpart:'Subpart C \u2014 Basic Hospital Functions',
intro:'The hospital must have a medical record service that has administrative responsibility for medical records. A medical record must be maintained for every individual evaluated or treated in the hospital.',
body:[
{type:'std',label:'(a)',title:'Standard: Organization and staffing.'},
{type:'text',text:'The organization of the medical record service must be appropriate to the scope and complexity of the services performed. The hospital must employ adequate personnel to ensure prompt completion, filing, and retrieval of records.',indent:0},
{type:'std',label:'(b)',title:'Standard: Form and retention of record.'},
{type:'text',text:'The hospital must maintain a medical record for each inpatient and outpatient. Medical records must be accurately written, promptly completed, properly filed and retained, and accessible. The hospital must use a system of author identification and record maintenance that ensures the integrity of the authentication and protects the security of all record entries.',indent:0},
{type:'p',label:'(1)',text:'Medical records must be retained in their original or legally reproduced form for a period of at least 5 years.',indent:1},
{type:'p',label:'(2)',text:'The hospital must have a system of coding and indexing medical records. The system must allow for timely retrieval by diagnosis and procedure, in order to support medical care evaluation studies.',indent:1},
{type:'p',label:'(3)',text:'The hospital must have a procedure for ensuring the confidentiality of patient records. Information from or copies of records may be released only to authorized individuals, and the hospital must ensure that unauthorized individuals cannot gain access to or alter patient records. Original medical records must be released by the hospital only in accordance with Federal or State laws, court orders, or subpoenas.',indent:1},
{type:'std',label:'(c)',title:'Standard: Content of record.'},
{type:'text',text:"The medical record must contain information to justify admission and continued hospitalization, support the diagnosis, and describe the patient's progress and response to medications and services.",indent:0},
{type:'p',label:'(1)',text:'All patient medical record entries must be legible, complete, dated, timed, and authenticated in written or electronic form by the person responsible for providing or evaluating the service provided, consistent with hospital policies and procedures.',indent:1},
{type:'p',label:'(2)',text:'All orders, including verbal orders, must be dated, timed, and authenticated promptly by the ordering practitioner or by another practitioner who is responsible for the care of the patient only if such a practitioner is acting in accordance with State law, including scope-of-practice laws, hospital policies, and medical staff bylaws, rules, and regulations.',indent:1},
{type:'p',label:'(3)',text:"Hospitals may use pre-printed and electronic standing orders, order sets, and protocols for patient orders only if the hospital:",indent:1},
{type:'p',label:'(i)',text:"Establishes that such orders and protocols have been reviewed and approved by the medical staff and the hospital's nursing and pharmacy leadership;",indent:2},
{type:'p',label:'(ii)',text:'Demonstrates that such orders and protocols are consistent with nationally recognized and evidence-based guidelines;',indent:2},
{type:'p',label:'(iii)',text:'Ensures that the periodic and regular review of such orders and protocols is conducted by the medical staff and the hospital\'s nursing and pharmacy leadership to determine the continuing usefulness and safety of the orders and protocols; and',indent:2},
{type:'p',label:'(iv)',text:"Ensures that such orders and protocols are dated, timed, and authenticated promptly in the patient's medical record by the ordering practitioner or by another practitioner responsible for the care of the patient.",indent:2},
{type:'p',label:'(4)',text:'All records must document the following, as appropriate:',indent:1},
{type:'p',label:'(i)',text:'Evidence of\u2014',indent:2},
{type:'p',label:'(A)',text:"A medical history and physical examination completed and documented no more than 30 days before or 24 hours after admission or registration, but prior to surgery or a procedure requiring anesthesia services. The medical history and physical examination must be placed in the patient's medical record within 24 hours after admission or registration, but prior to surgery or a procedure requiring anesthesia services.",indent:3},
{type:'p',label:'(B)',text:"An updated examination of the patient, including any changes in the patient's condition, when the medical history and physical examination are completed within 30 days before admission or registration. Documentation of the updated examination must be placed in the patient's medical record within 24 hours after admission or registration, but prior to surgery or a procedure requiring anesthesia services.",indent:3},
{type:'p',label:'(ii)',text:'Admitting diagnosis.',indent:2},
{type:'p',label:'(iii)',text:'Results of all consultative evaluations of the patient and appropriate findings by clinical and other staff involved in the care of the patient.',indent:2},
{type:'p',label:'(iv)',text:'Documentation of complications, hospital acquired infections, and unfavorable reactions to drugs and anesthesia.',indent:2},
{type:'p',label:'(v)',text:'Properly executed informed consent forms for procedures and treatments specified by the medical staff, or by Federal or State law if applicable, to require written patient consent.',indent:2},
{type:'p',label:'(vi)',text:"All practitioners' orders, nursing notes, reports of treatment, medication records, radiology, and laboratory reports, and vital signs and other information necessary to monitor the patient's condition.",indent:2},
{type:'p',label:'(vii)',text:'Discharge summary with outcome of hospitalization, disposition of case, and provisions for follow-up care.',indent:2},
{type:'p',label:'(viii)',text:'Final diagnosis with completion of medical records within 30 days following discharge.',indent:2},
{type:'std',label:'(d)',title:'Standard: Electronic notifications.'},
{type:'text',text:'If the hospital utilizes an electronic medical records system or other electronic administrative system, which is conformant with the content exchange standard at 45 CFR 170.205(d)(2), then the hospital must demonstrate that\u2014',indent:0},
{type:'p',label:'(1)',text:"The system's notification capacity is fully operational and the hospital uses it in accordance with all State and Federal statutes and regulations applicable to the hospital's exchange of patient health information.",indent:1},
{type:'p',label:'(2)',text:'The system sends notifications that must include at least patient name, treating practitioner name, and sending institution name.',indent:1},
{type:'p',label:'(3)',text:'The system sends notifications at the time of:',indent:1},
{type:'p',label:'(i)',text:"The patient's registration in the hospital's emergency department (if applicable).",indent:2},
{type:'p',label:'(ii)',text:"The patient's admission to the hospital's inpatient services (if applicable).",indent:2},
{type:'p',label:'(4)',text:'The system sends notifications either immediately prior to, or at the time of:',indent:1},
{type:'p',label:'(i)',text:"The patient's discharge or transfer from the hospital's emergency department (if applicable).",indent:2},
{type:'p',label:'(ii)',text:"The patient's discharge or transfer from the hospital's inpatient services (if applicable).",indent:2},
{type:'p',label:'(5)',text:"The hospital has made a reasonable effort to ensure that the system sends the notifications to all applicable post-acute care services providers and suppliers, as well as to any of the following practitioners and entities which need to receive notification of the patient's status for treatment, care coordination, or quality improvement purposes:",indent:1},
{type:'p',label:'(i)',text:"The patient's established primary care practitioner;",indent:2},
{type:'p',label:'(ii)',text:"The patient's established primary care practice group or entity; or",indent:2},
{type:'p',label:'(iii)',text:"Other practitioner, or other practice group or entity, identified by the patient as the practitioner, or practice group or entity, primarily responsible for his or her care.",indent:2},
]},
{id:'482.25',citation:'§\u00a0482.25',title:'Pharmaceutical Services',tags:['general'],subpart:'Subpart C \u2014 Basic Hospital Functions',
intro:'The hospital must have pharmaceutical services that meet the needs of the patients. The institution must have a pharmacy directed by a registered pharmacist or a drug storage area under competent supervision. The medical staff is responsible for developing policies and procedures that minimize drug errors.',
body:[
{type:'std',label:'(a)',title:'Standard: Pharmacy management and administration.'},
{type:'text',text:'The pharmacy or drug storage area must be administered in accordance with accepted professional principles.',indent:0},
{type:'p',label:'(1)',text:'A full-time, part-time, or consulting pharmacist must be responsible for developing, supervising, and coordinating all the activities of the pharmacy services.',indent:1},
{type:'p',label:'(2)',text:'The pharmaceutical service must have an adequate number of personnel to ensure quality pharmaceutical services, including emergency services.',indent:1},
{type:'p',label:'(3)',text:'Current and accurate records must be kept of the receipt and disposition of all scheduled drugs.',indent:1},
{type:'std',label:'(b)',title:'Standard: Delivery of services.'},
{type:'text',text:'In order to provide patient safety, drugs and biologicals must be controlled and distributed in accordance with applicable standards of practice, consistent with Federal and State law.',indent:0},
{type:'p',label:'(1)',text:'All compounding, packaging, and dispensing of drugs and biologicals must be under the supervision of a pharmacist and performed consistent with State and Federal laws.',indent:1},
{type:'p',label:'(2)',text:'',indent:1},
{type:'p',label:'(i)',text:'All drugs and biologicals must be kept in a secure area, and locked when appropriate.',indent:2},
{type:'p',label:'(ii)',text:'Drugs listed in Schedules II, III, IV, and V of the Comprehensive Drug Abuse Prevention and Control Act of 1970 must be kept locked within a secure area.',indent:2},
{type:'p',label:'(iii)',text:'Only authorized personnel may have access to locked areas.',indent:2},
{type:'p',label:'(3)',text:'Outdated, mislabeled, or otherwise unusable drugs and biologicals must not be available for patient use.',indent:1},
{type:'p',label:'(4)',text:'When a pharmacist is not available, drugs and biologicals must be removed from the pharmacy or storage area only by personnel designated in the policies of the medical staff and pharmaceutical service, in accordance with Federal and State law.',indent:1},
{type:'p',label:'(5)',text:'Drugs and biologicals not specifically prescribed as to time or number of doses must automatically be stopped after a reasonable time that is predetermined by the medical staff.',indent:1},
{type:'p',label:'(6)',text:"Drug administration errors, adverse drug reactions, and incompatibilities must be immediately reported to the attending physician and, if appropriate, to the hospital's QAPI program.",indent:1},
{type:'p',label:'(7)',text:'Abuses and losses of controlled substances must be reported, in accordance with applicable Federal and State laws, to the individual responsible for the pharmaceutical service, and to the chief executive officer, as appropriate.',indent:1},
{type:'p',label:'(8)',text:'Information relating to drug interactions and information of drug therapy, side effects, toxicology, dosage, indications for use, and routes of administration must be available to the professional staff.',indent:1},
{type:'p',label:'(9)',text:'A formulary system must be established by the medical staff to assure quality pharmaceuticals at reasonable costs.',indent:1},
]},
{id:'482.26',citation:'§\u00a0482.26',title:'Radiologic Services',tags:['general'],subpart:'Subpart C \u2014 Basic Hospital Functions',
intro:'The hospital must maintain, or have available, diagnostic radiologic services. If therapeutic services are also provided, they, as well as the diagnostic services, must meet professionally approved standards for safety and personnel qualifications.',
body:[
{type:'std',label:'(a)',title:'Standard: Radiologic services.'},
{type:'text',text:'The hospital must maintain, or have available, radiologic services according to the needs of the patients.',indent:0},
{type:'std',label:'(b)',title:'Standard: Safety for patients and personnel.'},
{type:'text',text:'The radiologic services, particularly ionizing radiology procedures, must be free from hazards for patients and personnel.',indent:0},
{type:'p',label:'(1)',text:'Proper safety precautions must be maintained against radiation hazards. This includes adequate shielding for patients, personnel, and facilities, as well as appropriate storage, use, and disposal of radioactive materials.',indent:1},
{type:'p',label:'(2)',text:'Periodic inspection of equipment must be made and hazards identified must be promptly corrected.',indent:1},
{type:'p',label:'(3)',text:'Radiation workers must be checked periodically, by the use of exposure meters or badge tests, for amount of radiation exposure.',indent:1},
{type:'p',label:'(4)',text:'Radiologic services must be provided only on the order of practitioners with clinical privileges or, consistent with State law, of other practitioners authorized by the medical staff and the governing body to order the services.',indent:1},
{type:'std',label:'(c)',title:'Standard: Personnel.'},
{type:'p',label:'(1)',text:"A qualified full-time, part-time, or consulting radiologist must supervise the ionizing radiology services and must interpret only those radiologic tests that are determined by the medical staff to require a radiologist's specialized knowledge. For purposes of this section, a radiologist is a doctor of medicine or osteopathy who is qualified by education and experience in radiology.",indent:1},
{type:'p',label:'(2)',text:'Only personnel designated as qualified by the medical staff may use the radiologic equipment and administer procedures.',indent:1},
{type:'std',label:'(d)',title:'Standard: Records.'},
{type:'text',text:'Records of radiologic services must be maintained.',indent:0},
{type:'p',label:'(1)',text:'The radiologist or other practitioner who performs radiology services must sign reports of his or her interpretations.',indent:1},
{type:'p',label:'(2)',text:'The hospital must maintain the following for at least 5 years:',indent:1},
{type:'p',label:'(i)',text:'Copies of reports and printouts.',indent:2},
{type:'p',label:'(ii)',text:'Films, scans, and other image records, as appropriate.',indent:2},
]},
{id:'482.27',citation:'§\u00a0482.27',title:'Laboratory Services',tags:['general'],subpart:'Subpart C \u2014 Basic Hospital Functions',
intro:"The hospital must maintain, or have available, adequate laboratory services to meet the needs of its patients. The hospital must ensure that all laboratory services provided to its patients are performed in a facility certified in accordance with part 493 of this chapter.",
body:[
{type:'std',label:'(a)',title:'Standard: Adequacy of laboratory services.'},
{type:'text',text:'The hospital must have laboratory services available, either directly or through a contractual agreement with a certified laboratory that meets requirements of part 493 of this chapter.',indent:0},
{type:'p',label:'(1)',text:'Emergency laboratory services must be available 24 hours a day.',indent:1},
{type:'p',label:'(2)',text:'A written description of services provided must be available to the medical staff.',indent:1},
{type:'p',label:'(3)',text:'The laboratory must make provision for proper receipt and reporting of tissue specimens.',indent:1},
{type:'p',label:'(4)',text:'The medical staff and a pathologist must determine which tissue specimens require a macroscopic (gross) examination and which require both macroscopic and microscopic examinations.',indent:1},
{type:'std',label:'(b)',title:'Standard: Potentially infectious blood and blood components.'},
{type:'text',text:'If a hospital regularly uses the services of an outside blood collecting establishment, it must have an agreement with the blood collecting establishment that governs the procurement, transfer, and availability of blood and blood components. The agreement must require that the blood collecting establishment notify the hospital\u2014',indent:0},
{type:'p',label:'(i)',text:'Within 3 calendar days if the blood collecting establishment supplied blood and blood components collected from a donor who tested negative at the time of donation but tests reactive for evidence of HIV or HCV infection on a later donation or who is determined to be at increased risk for transmitting HIV or HCV infection;',indent:1},
{type:'p',label:'(ii)',text:'Within 45 days of the test, of the results of the supplemental (additional, more specific) test for HIV or HCV, as relevant, or other follow-up testing required by FDA; and',indent:1},
{type:'p',label:'(iii)',text:'Within 3 calendar days after the blood collecting establishment supplied blood and blood components collected from an infectious donor, whenever records are available.',indent:1},
]},
{id:'482.28',citation:'§\u00a0482.28',title:'Food and Dietetic Services',tags:['general'],subpart:'Subpart C \u2014 Basic Hospital Functions',
intro:'The hospital must have organized dietary services that are directed and staffed by adequate qualified personnel.',
body:[
{type:'std',label:'(a)',title:'Standard: Organization.'},
{type:'text',text:'The dietary service must have a director, qualified by training or experience in food service management, and a sufficient number of qualified supervisory and technical personnel. There must be a registered dietitian, with appropriate training and experience in therapeutic dietary practices, responsible for the nutritional care of patients.',indent:0},
{type:'std',label:'(b)',title:'Standard: Diets.'},
{type:'p',label:'(1)',text:'Menus must meet the needs of the patients.',indent:1},
{type:'p',label:'(2)',text:'Therapeutic diets must be prescribed by the practitioner responsible for the care of the patients.',indent:1},
{type:'p',label:'(3)',text:'The food must be prepared by methods that conserve nutritive value, flavor, and appearance.',indent:1},
{type:'p',label:'(4)',text:'Food and drink must be wholesome, palatable, free from spoilage.',indent:1},
{type:'p',label:'(5)',text:'The temperature of the food when it is served must maintain safe food handling standards.',indent:1},
{type:'p',label:'(6)',text:'There must be a 24-hour supply of staple foods and a 3-day supply of perishables on hand.',indent:1},
]},
{id:'482.30',citation:'§\u00a0482.30',title:'Utilization Review',tags:['general'],subpart:'Subpart C \u2014 Basic Hospital Functions',
intro:'The hospital must have in effect a utilization review (UR) plan that provides for review of services furnished by the institution and by members of the medical staff to patients entitled to benefits under the Medicare and Medicaid programs.',
body:[
{type:'std',label:'(a)',title:'Standard: Applicability.'},
{type:'text',text:'The provisions of this section apply except in either of the following circumstances:',indent:0},
{type:'p',label:'(1)',text:'A Utilization and Quality Control Quality Improvement Organization (QIO) has assumed binding review for the hospital.',indent:1},
{type:'p',label:'(2)',text:'CMS has determined that the UR procedures established by the State under title XIX of the Act are superior to the procedures required in this section, and has required hospitals in that State to meet the UR plan requirements under §§ 456.50 through 456.245 of this chapter.',indent:1},
{type:'std',label:'(b)',title:'Standard: Composition of utilization review committee.'},
{type:'text',text:"A UR committee consisting of two or more practitioners must carry out the UR function. At least two of the members of the committee must be doctors of medicine or osteopathy. The committee must be one of the following:",indent:0},
{type:'p',label:'(1)',text:"A staff committee of the institution; or",indent:1},
{type:'p',label:'(2)',text:"A group outside the institution, e.g., the local medical society or a group of practitioners established by the local medical society.",indent:1},
{type:'text',text:"The committee's or group's reviews may not be conducted by any individual who\u2014",indent:0},
{type:'p',label:'(i)',text:'Has a direct financial interest (for example, an ownership interest) in that hospital; or',indent:1},
{type:'p',label:'(ii)',text:'Was professionally involved in the care of the patient whose case is being reviewed.',indent:1},
{type:'std',label:'(c)',title:'Standard: Scope and frequency of review.'},
{type:'p',label:'(1)',text:'The UR plan must provide for review for Medicare and Medicaid patients with respect to the medical necessity of\u2014',indent:1},
{type:'p',label:'(i)',text:'Admissions to the institution;',indent:2},
{type:'p',label:'(ii)',text:'The duration of stays; and',indent:2},
{type:'p',label:'(iii)',text:'Professional services furnished, including drugs and biologicals.',indent:2},
{type:'std',label:'(d)',title:'Standard: Extended stay review.'},
{type:'text',text:'The UR plan must provide for a review of the admissions and continued stays of patients who have reached a length of stay that requires extended review. A determination must be made as to whether continued stay is medically necessary.',indent:0},
{type:'std',label:'(e)',title:'Standard: Review of professional services.'},
{type:'text',text:'A review must be made of professional services rendered to determine medical necessity and to promote the most efficient use of available health facilities and services.',indent:0},
]},
{id:'482.41',citation:'§\u00a0482.41',title:'Physical Environment',tags:['general'],subpart:'Subpart C \u2014 Basic Hospital Functions',
intro:'The hospital must be constructed, arranged, and maintained to ensure the safety of the patient, and to provide facilities for diagnosis and treatment and for special hospital services appropriate to the needs of the community.',
body:[
{type:'std',label:'(a)',title:'Standard: Buildings.'},
{type:'text',text:'The condition of the physical plant and the overall hospital environment must be developed and maintained in such a manner that the safety and well-being of patients are assured. The hospital must meet the Life Safety Code of the National Fire Protection Association applicable to hospitals.',indent:0},
{type:'std',label:'(b)',title:'Standard: Life safety from fire.'},
{type:'text',text:'Except as otherwise provided in this section, the hospital must meet the applicable provisions of and must proceed in accordance with the Life Safety Code (NFPA 101). Buildings must be of safe construction.',indent:0},
{type:'std',label:'(c)',title:'Standard: Facilities.'},
{type:'text',text:"The hospital must maintain physical facilities appropriate to the hospital's services and patient population, including:",indent:0},
{type:'p',label:'(1)',text:'Adequate space for examination and treatment of patients.',indent:1},
{type:'p',label:'(2)',text:'Suitable bathroom facilities in the patient care areas.',indent:1},
{type:'p',label:'(3)',text:'Facilities for the isolation of patients as indicated by the infection prevention and control program.',indent:1},
{type:'p',label:'(4)',text:'Facilities for the safe handling and disposal of hazardous materials and waste.',indent:1},
]},
{id:'482.42',citation:'§\u00a0482.42',title:'Infection Prevention and Control & Antibiotic Stewardship',tags:['general'],subpart:'Subpart C \u2014 Basic Hospital Functions',
intro:'The hospital must have active hospital-wide programs for the surveillance, prevention, and control of HAIs and other infectious diseases, and for the optimization of antibiotic use through stewardship. The programs must demonstrate adherence to nationally recognized infection prevention and control guidelines, as well as to best practices for improving antibiotic use where applicable, and for reducing the development and transmission of HAIs and antibiotic-resistant organisms.',
body:[
{type:'std',label:'(a)',title:'Standard: Infection prevention and control program organization and policies.'},
{type:'text',text:'The hospital must demonstrate that:',indent:0},
{type:'p',label:'(1)',text:'An individual (or individuals), who is qualified through education, training, experience, or certification in infection prevention and control, is appointed by the governing body as the infection preventionist(s)/infection control professional(s) responsible for the infection prevention and control program.',indent:1},
{type:'p',label:'(2)',text:'The hospital infection prevention and control program, as documented in its policies and procedures, employs methods for preventing and controlling the transmission of infections within the hospital and between the hospital and other institutions and settings.',indent:1},
{type:'p',label:'(3)',text:'The infection prevention and control program includes a system for identifying, reporting, investigating, and controlling infections and communicable diseases of patients and personnel.',indent:1},
{type:'p',label:'(4)',text:'The results of the infection surveillance, prevention, and control program must be documented and reported to the appropriate authority periodically.',indent:1},
{type:'std',label:'(b)',title:'Standard: Antibiotic stewardship program.'},
{type:'text',text:'The hospital must have a hospital-wide antibiotic stewardship program that:',indent:0},
{type:'p',label:'(1)',text:'Demonstrates coordination among all components of the hospital responsible for antibiotic use and resistance, including, but not limited to, the infection prevention and control program, the QAPI program, the medical staff, nursing services, and pharmacy services.',indent:1},
{type:'p',label:'(2)',text:'Documents the evidence-based use of antibiotics in all departments and services of the hospital.',indent:1},
{type:'p',label:'(3)',text:'Documents any improvements, including sustained improvements, in proper antibiotic use.',indent:1},
{type:'p',label:'(4)',text:'Adheres to nationally recognized guidelines, as well as best practices, for improving antibiotic use.',indent:1},
{type:'p',label:'(5)',text:'Reflects the scope and complexity of the hospital services provided.',indent:1},
]},
{id:'482.43',citation:'§\u00a0482.43',title:'Discharge Planning',tags:['general'],subpart:'Subpart C \u2014 Basic Hospital Functions',
intro:"The hospital must have an effective discharge planning process that focuses on the patient's goals and treatment preferences and includes the patient and, when the patient agrees, the patient's caregivers in the development of the discharge plan.",
body:[
{type:'std',label:'(a)',title:'Standard: Identification of patients in need of discharge planning.'},
{type:'text',text:'The hospital must identify at an early stage of hospitalization all patients who are likely to suffer adverse health consequences upon discharge if there is no adequate discharge planning. Hospitals must provide a discharge planning evaluation for all patients identified as needing it and for other patients upon request.',indent:0},
{type:'std',label:'(b)',title:'Standard: Discharge planning evaluation.'},
{type:'text',text:'A registered nurse, social worker, or other appropriate qualified personnel must develop, or supervise the development of, the evaluation. The evaluation must include:',indent:0},
{type:'p',label:'(1)',text:"An evaluation of the patient's likely need for post-hospital services.",indent:1},
{type:'p',label:'(2)',text:"The availability of post-hospital services and the likelihood of the patient's access to those services.",indent:1},
{type:'p',label:'(3)',text:"The patient's goals and treatment preferences.",indent:1},
{type:'p',label:'(4)',text:"The patient's or the patient's caregiver's capacity and capabilities to perform required care.",indent:1},
{type:'std',label:'(c)',title:'Standard: Discharge plan.'},
{type:'text',text:"The hospital must develop a discharge plan for each patient identified as needing discharge planning. The discharge plan must be developed in collaboration with the patient and, when the patient agrees, with the patient's caregivers, consistent with the patient's goals and treatment preferences.",indent:0},
{type:'std',label:'(d)',title:'Standard: Reassessment.'},
{type:'text',text:"The hospital must reassess the patient's discharge plan if there are factors that may affect continuing care needs or the appropriateness of the discharge plan.",indent:0},
]},
{id:'482.45',citation:'§\u00a0482.45',title:'Organ, Tissue, and Eye Procurement',tags:['general'],subpart:'Subpart C \u2014 Basic Hospital Functions',
intro:"Hospitals must have and implement written protocols that incorporate an agreement with an OPO designated under § 486.307 of this chapter; incorporate an agreement with at least one tissue bank and at least one eye bank; ensure that the hospital's protocols are reviewed and updated periodically; and describe the criteria for referral of potential donors to the OPO.",
body:[
{type:'std',label:'(a)',title:'Standard: Organ procurement responsibilities.'},
{type:'text',text:"The hospital must have and implement written protocols that incorporate an agreement with an OPO. The hospital must notify the OPO, in a timely manner, of individuals whose death is imminent or who have died in the hospital. The hospital must ensure, in collaboration with the OPO, that the family of each potential donor is informed of the option to donate organs, tissues, or eyes.",indent:0},
{type:'std',label:'(b)',title:'Standard: Organ transplantation responsibilities.'},
{type:'text',text:'Transplant hospitals must be members of the Organ Procurement and Transplantation Network (OPTN) and must comply with the OPTN rules. The hospital must have a written agreement with a tissue bank and an eye bank to cooperate in the retrieval, processing, preservation, storage, and distribution of tissues and eyes.',indent:0},
]},

// ── SUBPART D ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
{id:'482.56',citation:'§ 482.56',title:'Rehabilitation Services',tags:['general'],subpart:'Subpart D — Optional Hospital Services',
intro:'If the hospital provides rehabilitation, physical therapy, occupational therapy, audiology, or speech pathology services, the services must be organized and staffed to ensure the health and safety of patients.',
body:[
{type:'std',label:'(a)',title:'Standard: Organization and staffing.'},
{type:'text',text:'The organization of the service must be appropriate to the scope of the services offered.',indent:0},
{type:'p',label:'(1)',text:'The director of the services must have the necessary knowledge, experience, and capabilities to properly supervise and administer the services.',indent:1},
{type:'p',label:'(2)',text:'Physical therapy, occupational therapy, speech-language pathology or audiology services, if provided, must be provided by qualified physical therapists, physical therapist assistants, occupational therapists, occupational therapy assistants, speech-language pathologists, or audiologists as defined in part 484 of this chapter.',indent:1},
{type:'std',label:'(b)',title:'Standard: Delivery of services.'},
{type:'text',text:'Services must only be provided under the orders of a qualified and licensed practitioner who is responsible for the care of the patient, acting within his or her scope of practice under applicable State law.',indent:0},
{type:'p',label:'(1)',text:"All rehabilitation services orders must be documented in the patient's medical record in accordance with the requirements at § 482.24.",indent:1},
{type:'p',label:'(2)',text:'The provision of care and the personnel qualifications must be in accordance with national acceptable standards of practice and must also meet the requirements of § 409.17 of this chapter.',indent:1},
]},
// ── SUBPART E ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
{id:'482.60',citation:'§\u00a0482.60',title:'Special Provisions Applying to Psychiatric Hospitals',tags:['psych'],subpart:'Subpart E \u2014 Psychiatric-Specific Requirements',
intro:'A psychiatric hospital must\u2014',
body:[
{type:'p',label:'(a)',text:'Be primarily engaged in providing, by or under the supervision of a doctor of medicine or osteopathy, psychiatric services for the diagnosis and treatment of mentally ill persons;',indent:0},
{type:'p',label:'(b)',text:'Meet the conditions of participation specified in §§ 482.1 through 482.23 and §§ 482.25 through 482.57;',indent:0},
{type:'p',label:'(c)',text:'Maintain clinical records on all patients, including records sufficient to permit CMS to determine the degree and intensity of treatment furnished to Medicare beneficiaries, as specified in § 482.61; and',indent:0},
{type:'p',label:'(d)',text:'Meet the staffing requirements specified in § 482.62.',indent:0},
]},
{id:'482.61',citation:'§\u00a0482.61',title:'Special Medical Record Requirements for Psychiatric Hospitals',tags:['psych'],subpart:'Subpart E \u2014 Psychiatric-Specific Requirements',
intro:'The medical records maintained by a psychiatric hospital must permit determination of the degree and intensity of the treatment provided to individuals who are furnished services in the institution.',
body:[
{type:'std',label:'(a)',title:'Standard: Development of assessment/diagnostic data.'},
{type:'text',text:'Medical records must stress the psychiatric components of the record, including history of findings and treatment provided for the psychiatric condition for which the patient is hospitalized.',indent:0},
{type:'p',label:'(1)',text:"The identification data must include the patient's legal status.",indent:1},
{type:'p',label:'(2)',text:'A provisional or admitting diagnosis must be made on every patient at the time of admission, and must include the diagnoses of intercurrent diseases as well as the psychiatric diagnoses.',indent:1},
{type:'p',label:'(3)',text:'The reasons for admission must be clearly documented as stated by the patient and/or others significantly involved.',indent:1},
{type:'p',label:'(4)',text:'The social service records, including reports of interviews with patients, family members, and others, must provide an assessment of home plans and family attitudes, and community resource contacts as well as a social history.',indent:1},
{type:'p',label:'(5)',text:'When indicated, a complete neurological examination must be recorded at the time of the admission physical examination.',indent:1},
{type:'std',label:'(b)',title:'Standard: Psychiatric evaluation.'},
{type:'text',text:'Each patient must receive a psychiatric evaluation that must\u2014',indent:0},
{type:'p',label:'(1)',text:'Be completed within 60 hours of admission;',indent:1},
{type:'p',label:'(2)',text:'Include a medical history;',indent:1},
{type:'p',label:'(3)',text:'Contain a record of mental status;',indent:1},
{type:'p',label:'(4)',text:'Note the onset of illness and the circumstances leading to admission;',indent:1},
{type:'p',label:'(5)',text:'Describe attitudes and behavior;',indent:1},
{type:'p',label:'(6)',text:'Estimate intellectual functioning, memory functioning, and orientation; and',indent:1},
{type:'p',label:'(7)',text:"Include an inventory of the patient's assets in descriptive, not interpretive, fashion.",indent:1},
{type:'std',label:'(c)',title:'Standard: Treatment plan.'},
{type:'p',label:'(1)',text:"Each patient must have an individual comprehensive treatment plan that must be based on an inventory of the patient's strengths and disabilities. The written plan must include\u2014",indent:1},
{type:'p',label:'(i)',text:'A substantiated diagnosis;',indent:2},
{type:'p',label:'(ii)',text:'Short-term and long-range goals;',indent:2},
{type:'p',label:'(iii)',text:'The specific treatment modalities utilized;',indent:2},
{type:'p',label:'(iv)',text:'The responsibilities of each member of the treatment team; and',indent:2},
{type:'p',label:'(v)',text:'Adequate documentation to justify the diagnosis and the treatment and rehabilitation activities carried out.',indent:2},
{type:'p',label:'(2)',text:'The treatment received by the patient must be documented in such a way to assure that all active therapeutic efforts are included.',indent:1},
{type:'std',label:'(d)',title:'Standard: Recording progress.'},
{type:'text',text:"Progress notes for the patient must be documented, in accordance with applicable State scope-of-practice laws and hospital policies, by the following qualified practitioners: Doctor(s) of medicine or osteopathy, or other licensed practitioner(s), who is responsible for the care of the patient; nurse(s) and social worker(s) (or social service staff) involved in the care of the patient; and, when appropriate, others significantly involved in the patient's active treatment modalities. The frequency of progress notes is determined by the condition of the patient but must be recorded at least weekly for the first 2 months and at least once a month thereafter and must contain recommendations for revisions in the treatment plan as indicated, as well as precise assessment of the patient's progress in accordance with the original or revised treatment plan.",indent:0},
{type:'std',label:'(e)',title:'Standard: Discharge planning and discharge summary.'},
{type:'text',text:"The record of each patient who has been discharged must have a discharge summary that includes a recapitulation of the patient's hospitalization and recommendations from appropriate services concerning follow-up or aftercare as well as a brief summary of the patient's condition on discharge.",indent:0},
{type:'std',label:'(f)',title:'Standard: Electronic notifications.'},
{type:'text',text:'If the hospital utilizes an electronic medical records system or other electronic administrative system, which is conformant with the content exchange standard at 45 CFR 170.205(d)(2), then the hospital must demonstrate that\u2014',indent:0},
{type:'p',label:'(1)',text:"The system's notification capacity is fully operational and the hospital uses it in accordance with all State and Federal statutes and regulations applicable to the hospital's exchange of patient health information.",indent:1},
{type:'p',label:'(2)',text:'The system sends notifications that must include at least patient name, treating practitioner name, and sending institution name.',indent:1},
{type:'p',label:'(3)',text:'The system sends notifications at the time of:',indent:1},
{type:'p',label:'(i)',text:"The patient's registration in the hospital's emergency department (if applicable).",indent:2},
{type:'p',label:'(ii)',text:"The patient's admission to the hospital's inpatient services (if applicable).",indent:2},
{type:'p',label:'(4)',text:'The system sends notifications either immediately prior to, or at the time of:',indent:1},
{type:'p',label:'(i)',text:"The patient's discharge or transfer from the hospital's emergency department (if applicable).",indent:2},
{type:'p',label:'(ii)',text:"The patient's discharge or transfer from the hospital's inpatient services (if applicable).",indent:2},
{type:'p',label:'(5)',text:"The hospital has made a reasonable effort to ensure that the system sends the notifications to all applicable post-acute care services providers and suppliers, as well as to any of the following practitioners:",indent:1},
{type:'p',label:'(i)',text:"The patient's established primary care practitioner;",indent:2},
{type:'p',label:'(ii)',text:"The patient's established primary care practice group or entity; or",indent:2},
{type:'p',label:'(iii)',text:"Other practitioner, or other practice group or entity, identified by the patient as the practitioner primarily responsible for his or her care.",indent:2},
]},
{id:'482.62',citation:'§\u00a0482.62',title:'Special Staff Requirements for Psychiatric Hospitals',tags:['psych'],subpart:'Subpart E \u2014 Psychiatric-Specific Requirements',
intro:'The hospital must have adequate numbers of qualified professional and supportive staff to evaluate patients, formulate written, individualized comprehensive treatment plans, provide active treatment measures, and engage in discharge planning.',
body:[
{type:'std',label:'(a)',title:'Standard: Personnel.'},
{type:'text',text:'The hospital must employ or undertake to provide adequate numbers of qualified professional, technical, and consultative personnel to:',indent:0},
{type:'p',label:'(1)',text:'Evaluate patients;',indent:1},
{type:'p',label:'(2)',text:'Formulate written individualized, comprehensive treatment plans;',indent:1},
{type:'p',label:'(3)',text:'Provide active treatment measures; and',indent:1},
{type:'p',label:'(4)',text:'Engage in discharge planning.',indent:1},
{type:'std',label:'(b)',title:'Standard: Director of inpatient psychiatric services; medical staff.'},
{type:'text',text:'Inpatient psychiatric services must be under the supervision of a clinical director, service chief, or equivalent who is qualified to provide the leadership required for an intensive treatment program. The number and qualifications of doctors of medicine and osteopathy must be adequate to provide essential psychiatric services.',indent:0},
{type:'p',label:'(1)',text:'The clinical director, service chief, or equivalent must meet the training and experience requirements for examination by the American Board of Psychiatry and Neurology or the American Osteopathic Board of Neurology and Psychiatry.',indent:1},
{type:'p',label:'(2)',text:'The director must monitor and evaluate the quality and appropriateness of services and treatment provided by the medical staff.',indent:1},
{type:'std',label:'(c)',title:'Standard: Availability of medical personnel.'},
{type:'text',text:"Doctors of medicine or osteopathy and other appropriate professional personnel must be available to provide necessary medical and surgical diagnostic and treatment services. If medical and surgical diagnostic and treatment services are not available within the institution, the institution must have an agreement with an outside source of these services to ensure that they are immediately available or a satisfactory agreement must be established for transferring patients to a general hospital that participates in the Medicare program.",indent:0},
{type:'std',label:'(d)',title:'Standard: Nursing services.'},
{type:'text',text:"The hospital must have a qualified director of psychiatric nursing services. In addition to the director of nursing, there must be adequate numbers of registered nurses, licensed practical nurses, and mental health workers to provide nursing care necessary under each patient's active treatment program and to maintain progress notes on each patient.",indent:0},
{type:'p',label:'(1)',text:"The director of psychiatric nursing services must be a registered nurse who has a master's degree in psychiatric or mental health nursing, or its equivalent from a school of nursing accredited by the National League for Nursing, or be qualified by education and experience in the care of the mentally ill. The director must demonstrate competence to participate in interdisciplinary formulation of individual treatment plans; to give skilled nursing care and therapy; and to direct, monitor, and evaluate the nursing care furnished.",indent:1},
{type:'p',label:'(2)',text:"The staffing pattern must ensure the availability of a registered professional nurse 24 hours each day. There must be adequate numbers of registered nurses, licensed practical nurses, and mental health workers to provide the nursing care necessary under each patient's active treatment program.",indent:1},
{type:'std',label:'(e)',title:'Standard: Psychological services.'},
{type:'text',text:"The hospital must provide or have available psychological services to meet the needs of the patients.",indent:0},
{type:'std',label:'(f)',title:'Standard: Social services.'},
{type:'text',text:'There must be a director of social services who monitors and evaluates the quality and appropriateness of social services furnished. The services must be furnished in accordance with accepted standards of practice and established policies and procedures.',indent:0},
{type:'p',label:'(1)',text:"The director of the social work department or service must have a master's degree from an accredited school of social work or must be qualified by education and experience in the social services needs of the mentally ill. If the director does not hold a master's degree in social work, at least one staff member must have this qualification.",indent:1},
{type:'p',label:'(2)',text:'Social service staff responsibilities must include, but are not limited to, participating in discharge planning, arranging for follow-up care, and developing mechanisms for exchange of appropriate information with sources outside the hospital.',indent:1},
{type:'std',label:'(g)',title:'Standard: Therapeutic activities.'},
{type:'text',text:'The hospital must provide a therapeutic activities program.',indent:0},
{type:'p',label:'(1)',text:'The program must be appropriate to the needs and interests of patients and be directed toward restoring and maintaining optimal levels of physical and psychosocial functioning.',indent:1},
{type:'p',label:'(2)',text:"The number of qualified therapists, support personnel, and consultants must be adequate to provide comprehensive therapeutic activities consistent with each patient's active treatment program.",indent:1},
]},
];

const igData=[{"id":"ig-482-1","citation":"§ 482.1","title":"Basis and Scope","tag":"general","source":"SOM Appendix A","link":"https://www.cms.gov/regulations-and-guidance/guidance/manuals/downloads/som107ap_a_hospitals.pdf","body":[{"type":"std","text":"A-0008 | Interpretive Guidelines"},{"type":"p","text":"In order to qualify for a provider agreement as a hospital under Medicare and Medicaid, an entity must meet and continue to meet all statutory provisions of § 1861(e) of the Act. This requires the entity to: be primarily engaged in providing diagnostic and therapeutic services or rehabilitation services to inpatients under physician supervision; maintain clinical records on all patients; have medical staff bylaws; require every Medicare patient to be under the care of a licensed practitioner; provide 24-hour nursing services rendered or supervised by an RN; have an operational utilization review plan; have a discharge planning process; be licensed if in a state that licenses hospitals; and meet all other requirements the Secretary finds necessary."},{"type":"p","text":"'Primarily engaged' means the hospital is directly providing inpatient services to inpatients. Capacity or potential capacity is not sufficient. CMS considers multiple factors in totality including: average daily census (ADC), average length of stay (ALOS), number of off-campus outpatient locations, number of provider-based emergency departments, number of inpatient beds relative to facility size and services, volume of outpatient vs. inpatient surgical procedures, staffing patterns, and ADC patterns by day of week. A minimum ALOS of two midnights and an ADC of at least two are benchmarks. If a hospital does not have at least two inpatients at the time of survey, a survey will not be conducted."},{"type":"sp","text":"Survey Procedures §482.1(a)(1)"},{"type":"sp_p","text":"Verify there are at least two inpatients currently in the hospital at the time of survey. If yes, proceed with evaluating whether the hospital is primarily engaged in providing the requisite services of a hospital, as well as the Conditions of Participation."},{"type":"sp_p","text":"If there are currently no inpatients, ask to see: ADC over the last 12 months; ALOS over the last 12 months; number of provider-based off-campus emergency departments; volume of outpatient surgical procedures compared to inpatient surgical procedures; staffing schedules by day of week and shift; number of inpatient beds in relation to the size of the facility and services offered."}]},{"id":"ig-482-11","citation":"§ 482.11","title":"Compliance with Federal, State and Local Laws","tag":"general","source":"SOM Appendix A","link":"https://www.cms.gov/regulations-and-guidance/guidance/manuals/downloads/som107ap_a_hospitals.pdf","body":[{"type":"std","text":"A-0020 | Interpretive Guidelines"},{"type":"p","text":"The hospital must ensure compliance with all applicable Federal, State, and local laws related to patient health and safety. Surveyors should interview the CEO or designee to determine compliance with Federal laws and refer or report noncompliance to the appropriate agency having jurisdiction (e.g., OSHA for bloodborne pathogen, standard precautions, or TB issues; EPA for hazardous chemical/waste issues)."},{"type":"std","text":"§ 482.11(b) — State Licensure (A-0022)"},{"type":"p","text":"Hospitals must be licensed under State law or approved as meeting State standards for licensing. A facility may have a State license but still not meet the Medicare definition of a hospital—the Medicare and State licensure criteria are separate. The definition of a hospital and the issue of whether the facility is 'Primarily Engaged' do not apply to Critical Access Hospitals."},{"type":"sp","text":"Survey Procedures §482.11(b)"},{"type":"sp_p","text":"Prior to the survey, determine whether the hospital has a current license by the state or local authority, or if in a State that does not license hospitals, verify that the responsible State agency has approved the hospital as meeting the State's established standards for licensure."},{"type":"std","text":"§ 482.11(c) — Personnel Standards (A-0023)"},{"type":"p","text":"All personnel required by State law to be licensed must possess a current license. The hospital must assure compliance with State licensure laws for all applicable staff (nurses, MD/DOs, physician assistants, dieticians, x-ray technologists, dentists, physical therapists, occupational therapists, respiratory therapists, hospital administrators). Staff must also meet certification requirements, minimum qualifications, training/education requirements, and permits (e.g., food handler permits). For telemedicine, practitioners must be licensed in both the state where they are located and the state where the patient is located."},{"type":"sp","text":"Survey Procedures §482.11(c)"},{"type":"sp_p","text":"Verify that for personnel required to be licensed, certified, and/or permitted by the State, the hospital has established and follows procedures for determining that personnel are properly licensed, certified, and/or permitted."},{"type":"sp_p","text":"Review a sample of personnel files to verify that licensure and/or other required credentials information is up to date."}]},{"id":"ig-482-12","citation":"§ 482.12","title":"Governing Body","tag":"general","source":"SOM Appendix A","link":"https://www.cms.gov/regulations-and-guidance/guidance/manuals/downloads/som107ap_a_hospitals.pdf","body":[{"type":"std","text":"A-0043 | Condition-Level Guidance"},{"type":"p","text":"The hospital must have a governing body that is effective in carrying out its responsibilities for the conduct of the hospital. In the absence of an organized governing body, written documentation identifying the responsible individual(s) is required. The governing body holds ultimate responsibility for compliance with all CoPs. If a hospital system uses a single governing body for multiple separately certified hospitals, each hospital must independently demonstrate compliance with the CoPs and must operate its services separately."},{"type":"sp","text":"Survey Procedures §482.12"},{"type":"sp_p","text":"Verify that the hospital has an organized governing body or has written documentation that identifies the individual or individuals responsible for the conduct of the hospital operations."},{"type":"sp_p","text":"If the hospital is part of a hospital system using one governing body for several separately certified hospitals, review the governing body minutes to determine if it is clear which actions pertain to which hospitals. Select several policy and procedure documents to determine if they clearly apply to the hospital being surveyed."},{"type":"std","text":"§ 482.12(a) — Medical Staff (A-0044–A-0053)"},{"type":"para","text":"(a)(1) Eligible Categories"},{"type":"p","text":"The governing body must determine which categories of practitioners are eligible for medical staff appointment, in accordance with State law. At minimum, the medical staff must include MDs or DOs. The governing body also has authority to grant medical staff privileges and membership to non-physician practitioners (nurse practitioners, clinical nurse specialists, certified registered nurse anesthetists, physician assistants, clinical social workers, clinical psychologists, etc.) in accordance with State law."},{"type":"sp","text":"Survey Procedures §482.12(a)(1)"},{"type":"sp_p","text":"Review documentation and verify that the governing body has determined and stated the categories of physicians and practitioners eligible for appointment to the medical staff or for medical staff privileges."},{"type":"para","text":"(a)(2)–(a)(7) Appointments and Bylaws"},{"type":"p","text":"The governing body must: appoint medical staff members after considering existing medical staff recommendations; assure medical staff bylaws exist; approve bylaws, rules, and regulations; ensure the medical staff is accountable for quality of care; ensure selection criteria include individual character, competence, training, experience, and judgment; and ensure staff membership or privileges are never dependent solely on certification, fellowship, or membership in a specialty body."},{"type":"para","text":"(a)(8)–(a)(9) Telemedicine"},{"type":"p","text":"Written agreements for telemedicine services must specify responsibility for credentialing and privileging. For distant-site Medicare-participating hospitals, the distant-site governing body is responsible for meeting §§ 482.12(a)(1)–(a)(7) for its physicians. For distant-site telemedicine entities, the agreement must specify that the entity provides services in a manner permitting the hospital to comply with all applicable CoPs. The hospital's governing body must grant privileges to each telemedicine physician before they may provide services."},{"type":"sp","text":"Survey Procedures §482.12(a)(8)–(a)(9)"},{"type":"sp_p","text":"Ask the hospital's leadership whether it uses telemedicine services. If yes, ask to see a copy of the written agreement(s) with the distant-site hospital(s) or telemedicine entity(ies). Verify that each agreement includes the required elements concerning credentialing and privileging, and that the hospital has documentation indicating it granted privileges to each telemedicine physician and practitioner."},{"type":"para","text":"(a)(10) Direct Consultation with Medical Staff Leader"},{"type":"p","text":"The governing body must consult directly with the individual assigned responsibility for the organization and conduct of the medical staff, or his/her designee, at least twice per year (calendar or fiscal year). 'Direct consultation' means face-to-face or via synchronous telecommunications. Discussion must include matters related to the quality of medical care provided. For multi-hospital systems with a single governing body, consultations must occur with each hospital's medical staff leader."},{"type":"sp","text":"Survey Procedures §482.12(a)(10)"},{"type":"sp_p","text":"Ask the hospital's CEO how the hospital complies with the requirement for periodic consultations with the leader of the hospital's medical staff, or the leader's designee. Ask to see evidence that such consultations have occurred (e.g., meeting agendas and attendee lists, meeting minutes). Ask whether the hospital tracks these consultations by calendar year or fiscal year; ask to see a copy of the policy that establishes this."},{"type":"probe","text":"Probes §482.12(a)(10)"},{"type":"q","text":"Is there evidence that the consultations were 'direct'?"},{"type":"q","text":"Is there evidence that the governing body met with the medical staff leader or designee at least twice during the previous year?"},{"type":"q","text":"Is there evidence that the discussion concerned matters related to the quality of medical care in the hospital?"},{"type":"q","text":"Has the leader/designee ever requested a meeting in addition to those regularly scheduled to discuss a matter of urgent concern? If yes, did the governing body respond by setting up a meeting?"},{"type":"std","text":"§ 482.12(b) — Chief Executive Officer (A-0057)"},{"type":"p","text":"The governing body must appoint one chief executive officer responsible for managing the entire hospital. Only one CEO may be appointed."},{"type":"sp","text":"Survey Procedures §482.12(b)"},{"type":"sp_p","text":"Verify that the hospital has only one chief executive officer for the entire hospital, that the governing body has appointed the chief executive officer, and that the chief executive officer is responsible for managing the entire hospital."},{"type":"std","text":"§ 482.12(c) — Care of Patients (A-0063–A-0068)"},{"type":"p","text":"Every Medicare patient must be under the care of a licensed practitioner as defined by the regulation (MD/DO, doctor of dental surgery or dental medicine, doctor of podiatric medicine, doctor of optometry within authorized scope, chiropractor within authorized scope, or clinical psychologist). A MD/DO must be on duty or on call at all times. A MD/DO must be responsible for any medical or psychiatric problem of each Medicare patient that is present on admission or develops during hospitalization and is not specifically within the scope of practice of a non-MD/DO admitting practitioner."},{"type":"std","text":"§ 482.12(d) — Institutional Plan and Budget (A-0073–A-0077)"},{"type":"p","text":"The institution must have an overall institutional plan that includes: an annual operating budget prepared per generally accepted accounting principles with all anticipated income and expenses; a capital expenditure plan for at least a 3-year period; detailed objectives and financing sources for capital expenditures exceeding $600,000 for land acquisition, improvements, or building/equipment replacement/modernization/expansion. The plan must be submitted to the designated planning agency for review, reviewed and updated annually, and prepared under governing body direction by a committee including representatives of the governing body, administrative staff, and medical staff."},{"type":"std","text":"§ 482.12(e) — Contracted Services (A-0083–A-0085)"},{"type":"p","text":"The governing body is responsible for all services furnished in the hospital whether or not provided under contract. The governing body must ensure every contracted service is provided in a safe and effective manner and permits the hospital to comply with all applicable CoPs. Patient care services under contract are subject to the same hospital-wide QAPI evaluation as services provided directly by the hospital. The hospital must maintain a list of all contracted services including scope and nature."},{"type":"std","text":"§ 482.12(f) — Emergency Services (A-0091–A-0094)"},{"type":"p","text":"If emergency services are provided at the hospital, the hospital must comply with § 482.55. If emergency services are not provided, the governing body must assure medical staff has written policies and procedures for appraisal of emergencies, initial treatment, and referral when appropriate—applicable 24/7 and hospital-wide. If emergency services are provided at the hospital but not at one or more off-campus departments, the governing body must assure policies and procedures exist for those off-campus locations for appraisal of emergencies and referral."},{"type":"sp","text":"Survey Procedures §482.12(f)(2)"},{"type":"sp_p","text":"Verify that the medical staff has adopted written policies and procedures for the management of medical emergencies. Review emergency care policies and procedures; confirm they are consistent with expectations for appraisal, initial treatment, and referral, and that they address emergency procedures for all on-campus and off-campus locations. Interview hospital staff at various locations: can they state their duties and what they are to do if an individual seeks or needs emergency care at their location?"}]},{"id":"ig-482-13","citation":"§ 482.13","title":"Patient's Rights","tag":"general","source":"SOM Appendix A","link":"https://www.cms.gov/regulations-and-guidance/guidance/manuals/downloads/som107ap_a_hospitals.pdf","body":[{"type":"std","text":"A-0115 | Condition-Level Guidance"},{"type":"p","text":"These requirements apply to all Medicare/Medicaid participating hospitals including short-term, acute care, surgical, specialty, psychiatric, rehabilitation, long-term, children's, and cancer hospitals. They apply to all parts and locations (outpatient services, provider-based entities, inpatient services) of the Medicare-participating hospital. Survey of the Patient Rights CoP should be coordinated by one surveyor, with each surveyor assessing compliance during their survey assignments."},{"type":"std","text":"§ 482.13(a) — Notice of Rights (A-0117)"},{"type":"p","text":"The hospital must inform each patient, or when appropriate the patient's representative (as allowed under State law), of the patient's rights in advance of furnishing or discontinuing patient care whenever possible. Notice must be provided before care is furnished, unless it is an emergency. The hospital must document that the patient or representative was informed."},{"type":"std","text":"§ 482.13(b) — Exercise of Rights"},{"type":"p","text":"The patient or, as permitted by State law, the patient's representative has the right to make informed decisions regarding care. The hospital must establish a clear policy on patient representatives. Patient representatives may exercise patient rights only to the extent permitted by State law. The hospital must comply with patient advance directives and must not condition care or discriminate against patients based on the presence or absence of an advance directive."},{"type":"std","text":"§ 482.13(c) — Privacy and Safety (A-0143–A-0154)"},{"type":"p","text":"Patients have the right to personal privacy and to receive care in a safe setting free from all forms of abuse, neglect, and harassment. The hospital must prohibit and take actions to prevent restraint and seclusion (physical and chemical) from being used as a means of coercion, discipline, convenience, or retaliation. Restraint and seclusion may be used only when less restrictive interventions have been determined to be ineffective to protect the patient or others from harm."},{"type":"std","text":"§ 482.13(e) — Restraint or Seclusion (A-0167–A-0207)"},{"type":"p","text":"Restraint or seclusion may only be used when: (1) less restrictive interventions have been determined to be ineffective; (2) a patient's behavior is an immediate and serious danger to him/herself or others; (3) written protocols are in place; (4) a physician or LIP orders the restraint or seclusion; (5) there is ongoing monitoring of the patient by trained staff. All deaths associated with use of restraint or seclusion must be reported to CMS. Restraint or seclusion must be discontinued at the earliest possible time, regardless of the length of time specified in the order."},{"type":"std","text":"§ 482.13(f) — Seclusion in Psychiatric Settings (A-0208–A-0217)"},{"type":"p","text":"In psychiatric inpatient settings, additional requirements apply: a face-to-face evaluation by a physician or LIP must occur within one hour of initiation; a registered nurse trained per § 482.13(f)(2)(ii) may conduct the one-hour evaluation; original orders may not exceed 4 hours for adults, 2 hours for children 9–17, or 1 hour for children under 9; orders must not be written as standing or PRN orders."},{"type":"std","text":"§ 482.13(g) — Death Reporting (A-0218)"},{"type":"p","text":"The hospital must report to CMS any death that occurs while a patient is in restraint or seclusion, within one hour of restraint/seclusion, or within 24 hours of removal from restraint or seclusion if there is reasonable suspicion that the use of restraint or seclusion contributed to the patient's death."},{"type":"std","text":"§ 482.13(h) — Advance Directives (A-0246–A-0249)"},{"type":"p","text":"The hospital must maintain written policies and procedures for advance directives, inform all adult patients of their rights regarding advance directives at the time of admission, document in the medical record whether an advance directive exists, not condition care on the presence or absence of an advance directive, and not discriminate against patients based on advance directive status. If the hospital cannot implement a patient's advance directive due to conscience, it must inform the patient and ensure the patient is transferred as necessary."}]},{"id":"ig-482-15","citation":"§ 482.15","title":"Emergency Preparedness","tag":"general","source":"SOM Appendix A","link":"https://www.cms.gov/regulations-and-guidance/guidance/manuals/downloads/som107ap_a_hospitals.pdf","body":[{"type":"std","text":"Condition-Level Guidance"},{"type":"p","text":"The hospital must comply with all applicable Federal, State, and local emergency preparedness requirements. The hospital must establish and maintain a comprehensive emergency preparedness program designed to ensure the safety and well-being of each patient during an emergency."},{"type":"p","text":"The emergency preparedness program must include: (1) a risk assessment and emergency plan that includes strategies for addressing emergency events identified by the risk assessment; (2) policies and procedures; (3) a communication plan; and (4) a training and testing program. The emergency plan must be reviewed and updated at least every 2 years."},{"type":"p","text":"The communication plan must include a system for communicating with hospital staff, the State and local public health department, other healthcare providers, and patients and their families. The hospital must maintain a list of the hospital's occupants as well as contact information for other healthcare facilities to facilitate interagency communication."},{"type":"sp","text":"Training and Testing Requirements"},{"type":"sp_p","text":"The hospital must conduct training that includes simulation exercises of emergencies. Annual training must include full-scale exercises that are community-based or individual facility-based functional exercises. The hospital must analyze the results of each exercise and make improvements as necessary. Staff must be trained in their roles within the emergency plan."}]},{"id":"ig-482-21","citation":"§ 482.21","title":"Quality Assessment and Performance Improvement (QAPI)","tag":"general","source":"SOM Appendix A","link":"https://www.cms.gov/regulations-and-guidance/guidance/manuals/downloads/som107ap_a_hospitals.pdf","body":[{"type":"std","text":"Condition-Level Guidance"},{"type":"p","text":"The hospital's QAPI program must reflect the complexity of its organization and services; involve all hospital departments and services including those under contract or arrangement; and focus on indicators related to improved health outcomes and prevention and reduction of medical errors. The hospital must maintain and demonstrate evidence of its QAPI program for review by CMS."},{"type":"p","text":"The program must include an ongoing program showing measurable improvement in indicators for which there is evidence that improvement will lead to better health outcomes. The hospital must measure, analyze, and track quality indicators including adverse patient events and other performance aspects that assess processes of care, hospital service, and operations."},{"type":"p","text":"Key requirements: (1) The program must be facility-wide, incorporating every service and activity; (2) departments must report to and receive reports from the facility's central QAPI body; (3) the program must identify opportunities for improvement and address safety issues; (4) a patient safety program must be implemented; (5) the governing body must be periodically apprised of QAPI program activities."}]},{"id":"ig-482-22","citation":"§ 482.22","title":"Medical Staff","tag":"general","source":"SOM Appendix A","link":"https://www.cms.gov/regulations-and-guidance/guidance/manuals/downloads/som107ap_a_hospitals.pdf","body":[{"type":"std","text":"Condition-Level Guidance"},{"type":"p","text":"The medical staff is responsible for the quality of medical care provided to patients and must be well organized with bylaws, rules, and regulations. The medical staff must be accountable to the governing body. At minimum, the medical staff must be composed of MDs or DOs; other practitioners may be granted membership/privileges in accordance with State law and governing body determination."},{"type":"p","text":"Credentialing and privileging must be based on: individual character, competence, training, experience, and judgment. The hospital must have a process for ongoing professional practice evaluation (OPPE) and focused professional practice evaluation (FPPE) for all practitioners with privileges. For telemedicine services, the hospital may exercise a streamlined privileging option relying on the distant-site hospital's or telemedicine entity's credentialing decisions."},{"type":"p","text":"The medical staff must have an identifiable leader (or leaders) assigned responsibility for the organization and conduct of the medical staff. Medical staff oversight functions must include: reviewing and acting on information from the QAPI program; enforcing its bylaws; providing information about quality of care to the governing body; and taking action to address identified quality problems."}]},{"id":"ig-482-23","citation":"§ 482.23","title":"Nursing Services","tag":"general","source":"SOM Appendix A","link":"https://www.cms.gov/regulations-and-guidance/guidance/manuals/downloads/som107ap_a_hospitals.pdf","body":[{"type":"std","text":"Condition-Level Guidance"},{"type":"p","text":"The hospital must have an organized nursing service that provides 24-hour nursing care to patients. A registered nurse must supervise and evaluate the nursing care for each patient and be immediately available for bedside care of any patient. The nursing service must be directed by a qualified RN (Director of Nursing)."},{"type":"p","text":"Staffing requirements: Nursing personnel must be sufficient to provide nursing care to all patients as needed. The charge nurse of each unit must be an RN. A licensed practical nurse or registered professional nurse must be on duty at all times. Personnel on all shifts must be licensed as required by State law."},{"type":"p","text":"Drug administration: Drugs and biologicals must be prepared and administered in accordance with Federal and State laws and the medical staff's approved policies and procedures. Only personnel authorized under State law may administer drugs and biologicals. Transfusions must be preceded by informed consent and may be administered only in accordance with State law and accepted standards of practice."},{"type":"p","text":"Patient care planning: Each patient must have a nursing care plan reflecting the patient's care needs. Nursing staff must assess patients' nursing care needs and ensure that nursing care plans are developed, implemented, and revised as needed."}]},{"id":"ig-482-24","citation":"§ 482.24","title":"Medical Record Services","tag":"general","source":"SOM Appendix A","link":"https://www.cms.gov/regulations-and-guidance/guidance/manuals/downloads/som107ap_a_hospitals.pdf","body":[{"type":"std","text":"Condition-Level Guidance"},{"type":"p","text":"The hospital must have a medical record service with administrative responsibility for medical records. A medical record must be maintained for every inpatient and outpatient. Medical records must be accurately written, promptly completed, properly filed and retained, and accessible."},{"type":"p","text":"Content requirements: Every medical record must contain: patient identification data; admission date; history and physical; chief complaint; details of examination and findings; final diagnosis with completion of medical records within 30 days following patient discharge; all practitioners' orders; nursing notes; reports of procedures and tests; medication administration records; and discharge summary."},{"type":"p","text":"Authentication: All entries must be legible and complete, and must be authenticated and dated promptly by the person (identified by name and discipline) responsible for ordering, providing, or evaluating the service furnished. Verbal orders must be authenticated by the author within the time frame specified by hospital medical staff policy."},{"type":"p","text":"Retention: The hospital must retain records for the period required by State law; if no State law governs, records must be retained for at least five years, or in the case of minors, three years after reaching majority under State law."}]},{"id":"ig-482-25","citation":"§ 482.25","title":"Pharmaceutical Services","tag":"general","source":"SOM Appendix A","link":"https://www.cms.gov/regulations-and-guidance/guidance/manuals/downloads/som107ap_a_hospitals.pdf","body":[{"type":"std","text":"Condition-Level Guidance"},{"type":"p","text":"The hospital must have pharmaceutical services that meet the needs of patients, directed by a registered pharmacist. Pharmacy and therapeutics functions must be organized to ensure appropriate and rational drug use. The pharmacy must be staffed with sufficient pharmacists and support personnel."},{"type":"p","text":"Drug storage and control: Drugs must be controlled and distributed in accordance with applicable State and Federal laws and regulations. All drugs and biologicals must be kept in a secure area. Medications requiring refrigeration must be stored at appropriate temperatures. Controlled substances must be stored in locked areas and inventoried according to Federal and State requirements."},{"type":"p","text":"Medication orders: Drug orders must be issued only by practitioners with prescribing authority under State law. The hospital must review the medication regimen of each patient. Drug errors, adverse drug reactions, and incompatibilities must be reported to the attending physician. Automatic stop orders must comply with medical staff policy."},{"type":"p","text":"Formulary and drug use evaluation: The pharmacy and therapeutics committee (or equivalent) must oversee hospital formulary development and drug use evaluation. There must be a process for evaluating new medications and monitoring high-alert medications. The hospital must provide pharmaceutical information to physicians and hospital staff."}]},{"id":"ig-482-26","citation":"§ 482.26","title":"Radiologic Services","tag":"general","source":"SOM Appendix A","link":"https://www.cms.gov/regulations-and-guidance/guidance/manuals/downloads/som107ap_a_hospitals.pdf","body":[{"type":"std","text":"Condition-Level Guidance"},{"type":"p","text":"If the hospital provides radiologic services, they must meet the needs of patients in accordance with acceptable standards of practice. The services must be provided by, or under the supervision of, a qualified radiologist or other qualified practitioner licensed under applicable State law. Radiological services must be available 7 days per week and at night if the hospital provides emergency care."},{"type":"p","text":"Safety: The radiologic services must have radiation safety policies and procedures. Personnel performing radiologic services must be adequately trained and wear radiation dose monitoring devices as required. Equipment must be maintained in safe working order and calibrated according to applicable standards."},{"type":"p","text":"Reports: All radiologic examinations must be interpreted by, or in consultation with, a qualified radiologist. Written reports of the radiologist's interpretation must be provided to the requesting practitioner and maintained in the patient's medical record."}]},{"id":"ig-482-27","citation":"§ 482.27","title":"Laboratory Services","tag":"general","source":"SOM Appendix A","link":"https://www.cms.gov/regulations-and-guidance/guidance/manuals/downloads/som107ap_a_hospitals.pdf","body":[{"type":"std","text":"Condition-Level Guidance"},{"type":"p","text":"The hospital must maintain or have available adequate laboratory services to meet the needs of its patients. Laboratory services must be provided by a laboratory that meets the requirements of 42 CFR Part 493 (CLIA '88). Emergency laboratory services must be available 24 hours per day, seven days per week."},{"type":"p","text":"If laboratory services are not provided on-site, the hospital must have written arrangements with certified or approved laboratories. The hospital must establish evaluation and accountability mechanisms to ensure contracted laboratory services meet laboratory requirements and standards. Laboratory reports must be incorporated into the patient's medical record."},{"type":"p","text":"Blood and blood products: The hospital must have adequate blood banking services. The hospital must have policies and procedures for blood transfusions and the prevention of transfusion errors. There must be systems to identify patients and confirm blood product compatibility before administration."}]},{"id":"ig-482-28","citation":"§ 482.28","title":"Food and Dietetic Services","tag":"general","source":"SOM Appendix A","link":"https://www.cms.gov/regulations-and-guidance/guidance/manuals/downloads/som107ap_a_hospitals.pdf","body":[{"type":"std","text":"Condition-Level Guidance"},{"type":"p","text":"The hospital must have organized food and dietetic services directed and staffed by adequate qualified personnel. A qualified dietitian (full-time, part-time, or consulting) must be responsible for the diet therapy program. The dietetic services must be sufficient to meet the nutritional needs of patients consistent with their clinical conditions and in accordance with accepted standards of practice."},{"type":"p","text":"Nutritional care: A nutritional assessment must be performed for each patient as indicated. The dietitian must develop and approve individualized therapeutic diets when ordered. The hospital must provide special diets, including medically required diets, as required by individual patient needs. Food must be prepared using sanitary techniques and in accordance with all applicable sanitation and food safety standards."},{"type":"p","text":"Menus: Menus must meet the nutritional needs of patients in accordance with their conditions. Therapeutic diets must be prescribed by the practitioner responsible for the patient's care. Patients must have an adequate choice of food and the hospital must accommodate dietary preferences to the extent possible."}]},{"id":"ig-482-30","citation":"§ 482.30","title":"Utilization Review","tag":"general","source":"SOM Appendix A","link":"https://www.cms.gov/regulations-and-guidance/guidance/manuals/downloads/som107ap_a_hospitals.pdf","body":[{"type":"std","text":"Condition-Level Guidance"},{"type":"p","text":"The hospital must have a utilization review (UR) plan that provides for review of services furnished by the institution and by members of the medical staff to Medicare and Medicaid patients. The purpose of UR is to ensure appropriate use of hospital resources."},{"type":"p","text":"The UR plan must include: the UR committee; the scope and frequency of review; criteria to be used in review; procedures for reviewing medical necessity of admissions, extended stays, and professional services; and methods for reporting findings to the governing body and medical staff."},{"type":"p","text":"The UR committee must consist of two or more practitioners who are not regular employees of the hospital. The committee must include MDs or DOs. The medical staff or committee must conduct timely review of admissions and continued stays. Findings and recommendations must be communicated to the attending practitioner and to hospital administration."}]},{"id":"ig-482-41","citation":"§ 482.41","title":"Physical Environment","tag":"general","source":"SOM Appendix A","link":"https://www.cms.gov/regulations-and-guidance/guidance/manuals/downloads/som107ap_a_hospitals.pdf","body":[{"type":"std","text":"Condition-Level Guidance"},{"type":"p","text":"The hospital must be constructed, arranged, and maintained to ensure the safety of the patient, and to provide facilities for diagnosis and treatment, and for special hospital services appropriate to the needs of the community. Compliance requires adherence to applicable Life Safety Code (LSC) standards and physical environment standards."},{"type":"p","text":"Life Safety Code: The hospital must meet the applicable provisions of the 2012 Life Safety Code (NFPA 101) and the 2012 Health Care Facilities Code (NFPA 99), which address fire protection, means of egress, fire alarm systems, sprinkler systems, smoking policies, and emergency power systems. LSC deficiencies are cited under the physical environment CoP."},{"type":"p","text":"Maintenance: The hospital must maintain all facilities and equipment in a manner that protects the health and safety of patients and personnel. There must be a preventive maintenance program. Emergency and standby power systems must be maintained in accordance with NFPA standards."},{"type":"p","text":"Infection control environment: The physical plant and environment must be maintained in a way that supports infection prevention and control. Proper ventilation, lighting, and sanitation must be maintained throughout the facility."}]},{"id":"ig-482-42","citation":"§ 482.42","title":"Infection Prevention and Control; Antibiotic Stewardship","tag":"general","source":"SOM Appendix A","link":"https://www.cms.gov/regulations-and-guidance/guidance/manuals/downloads/som107ap_a_hospitals.pdf","body":[{"type":"std","text":"Condition-Level Guidance"},{"type":"p","text":"The hospital must provide a sanitary environment to avoid sources and transmission of infections and communicable diseases. There must be an active program for the prevention, control, and investigation of infections and communicable diseases. The infection control officer(s) must develop and implement policies governing control of infections and communicable diseases."},{"type":"p","text":"The infection control program must: (1) include surveillance activities to identify infection risks; (2) investigate outbreaks of infectious disease; (3) develop and monitor infection control policies and procedures; (4) conduct ongoing in-service training for all departments; (5) maintain records of infections and communicable diseases; and (6) analyze infection data for trends."},{"type":"std","text":"Antibiotic Stewardship Program"},{"type":"p","text":"The hospital must have an antibiotic stewardship program consistent with nationally recognized guidelines that includes: policies and procedures to monitor antibiotic use; education for staff and practitioners on antibiotic use; systems to identify and address adverse drug events related to antibiotic use; prevention of healthcare-associated infections (HAIs); and a leader with training and experience in antibiotic stewardship. The program must document its activities and report antibiotic use and resistance data."}]},{"id":"ig-482-43","citation":"§ 482.43","title":"Discharge Planning","tag":"general","source":"SOM Appendix A","link":"https://www.cms.gov/regulations-and-guidance/guidance/manuals/downloads/som107ap_a_hospitals.pdf","body":[{"type":"std","text":"Condition-Level Guidance"},{"type":"p","text":"The hospital must have a discharge planning process that focuses on the goals and treatment preferences of the patient. The discharge planning process must be consistent with the patient's goals for care and treatment preferences, ensure an effective transition from hospital to post-discharge care, and reduce factors leading to preventable adverse events after discharge."},{"type":"p","text":"Assessment: The hospital must identify, early in the patient's admission, those patients likely to suffer adverse health consequences upon discharge if there is no planning for post-discharge care. A discharge planning evaluation must be performed for all patients and must begin within 24 hours of admission. The evaluation must include an assessment of the patient's likely need for appropriate post-acute services."},{"type":"p","text":"Patient/family involvement: The hospital must involve the patient and family/support persons in the discharge planning process and must ensure they have sufficient information about post-discharge care options. The hospital must disclose required information regarding choices for post-acute care services that meet the patient's needs and goals for care."},{"type":"p","text":"Referral and transfer: The hospital must arrange for the initial implementation of the discharge plan and must reassess the plan as the patient's condition changes. The hospital must transfer to the appropriate post-acute service provider with all necessary medical information and must not limit or restrict referral options to post-acute providers."}]},{"id":"ig-482-45","citation":"§ 482.45","title":"Organ, Tissue and Eye Procurement","tag":"general","source":"SOM Appendix A","link":"https://www.cms.gov/regulations-and-guidance/guidance/manuals/downloads/som107ap_a_hospitals.pdf","body":[{"type":"std","text":"Condition-Level Guidance"},{"type":"p","text":"The hospital must have and implement written protocols that: (1) incorporate an agreement with an Organ Procurement Organization (OPO) designated under 42 CFR Part 486; (2) incorporate an agreement with at least one tissue bank and at least one eye bank; (3) ensure that potential donors are identified and referred to the OPO in a timely manner; (4) ensure that the hospital works cooperatively with the designated OPO, tissue bank, and eye bank in the donation and procurement process."},{"type":"p","text":"Notification: The hospital must notify the OPO in a timely manner about all individuals whose death is imminent or who have died in the hospital. Written agreements must describe each party's responsibilities in the donation process and must ensure that the hospital's OPO-designated service area is covered."},{"type":"p","text":"Consent: The hospital must ensure that the family or next-of-kin of potential organ/tissue/eye donors is informed of the option to donate and is referred to the OPO for further information. The hospital must have a protocol for ensuring that all families of potential donors are offered the opportunity to donate. Donation must not compromise the medical care of a patient."}]},{"id":"ig-482-56","citation":"§ 482.56","title":"Rehabilitation Services","tag":"general","source":"SOM Appendix A","link":"https://www.cms.gov/regulations-and-guidance/guidance/manuals/downloads/som107ap_a_hospitals.pdf","body":[{"type":"std","text":"Condition-Level Guidance"},{"type":"p","text":"If the hospital provides rehabilitation services, the services must meet the needs of patients in accordance with acceptable standards of practice. The scope and organization of rehabilitation services must be appropriate to the needs of the patients served and must include appropriate policies and procedures."},{"type":"std","text":"§ 482.56(a) — Organization and Staffing"},{"type":"para","text":"(a)(1) Director Qualifications"},{"type":"p","text":"The rehabilitation services must be directed by a qualified professional who meets applicable regulations and standards for professional practice in the specific therapy discipline. The director must have training and experience in the specific rehabilitation discipline and in the management and administration of a rehabilitation program."},{"type":"para","text":"(a)(2) Qualified Therapists"},{"type":"p","text":"Rehabilitation services must be provided by qualified therapists, assistants, and support personnel. Therapists must be licensed or registered by the appropriate State licensing authority where State law provides for such licensing. Personnel must practice within the scope of their licensure or certification."},{"type":"std","text":"§ 482.56(b) — Delivery of Services"},{"type":"para","text":"(b)(1) Medical Record Documentation"},{"type":"p","text":"All rehabilitation services provided to patients must be documented in the patient's medical record, including: evaluation/assessment findings; treatment goals; the treatment plan; the patient's response to treatment; and progress toward goals. Documentation must reflect the individualized nature of the treatment plan and must be completed in a timely manner."},{"type":"para","text":"(b)(2) Standards of Practice"},{"type":"p","text":"Rehabilitation services must be provided in accordance with national standards of practice for the specific therapy discipline. Services must be consistent with the patient's diagnosis, needs, and goals. The rehabilitation program must coordinate with other hospital services to ensure integrated, comprehensive patient care."}]},{"id":"ig-482-60","citation":"§ 482.60","title":"Special Provisions Applying to Psychiatric Hospitals","tag":"psych","source":"SOM Appendix AA","link":"https://www.cms.gov/regulations-and-guidance/guidance/manuals/downloads/som107ap_aa_psyc_hospitals.pdf","body":[{"type":"std","text":"B98–B102 | Condition-Level Guidance"},{"type":"p","text":"(a) A hospital will be deemed to meet the 'primarily engaged' standard if it meets the clinical records requirement of (c) and the staffing requirements of (d)."},{"type":"p","text":"(b) The hospital must either be accredited by The Joint Commission or AOA, or independently meet the general hospital CoPs at §§ 482.1–482.23 and 482.25–482.57."},{"type":"p","text":"(c) Clinical records must be sufficient to permit CMS to determine the degree and intensity of treatment furnished to Medicare beneficiaries, as specified in § 482.61."},{"type":"p","text":"(d) Staffing requirements as specified in § 482.62 must be met."}]},{"id":"ig-482-61","citation":"§ 482.61","title":"Special Medical Record Requirements","tag":"psych","source":"SOM Appendix AA","link":"https://www.cms.gov/regulations-and-guidance/guidance/manuals/downloads/som107ap_aa_psyc_hospitals.pdf","body":[{"type":"std","text":"B103 | Condition-Level Guidance"},{"type":"p","text":"The clinical record must provide information indicating: need for admission and treatment; treatment goals; changes in treatment status; discharge planning; follow-up; and outcomes experienced by patients."},{"type":"p","text":"The structure and content must be an accurate functional representation of the patient's actual experience in the facility—containing enough information to demonstrate that the facility knows the patient's status, has adequate plans to intervene, and provides sufficient evidence of the effects of intervention."},{"type":"std","text":"§ 482.61(a) — Development of Assessment/Diagnostic Data (B104–B109)"},{"type":"p","text":"Medical records must stress the psychiatric components of the record, including history of findings and treatment provided for the psychiatric condition for which the patient is hospitalized."},{"type":"para","text":"(a)(1) Legal Status"},{"type":"p","text":"Legal status is defined by State statutes and dictates the circumstances under which the patient was admitted and/or is being treated (e.g., voluntary, involuntary, court-committed). Surveyors should determine through interview the terminology the facility uses for legal status and confirm that required evaluation and recertification documentation is present. Changes in legal status must be recorded with the date of change."},{"type":"para","text":"(a)(2) Provisional/Admitting Diagnosis"},{"type":"p","text":"An admission or working psychiatric diagnosis (including rule-out diagnoses), written in DSM or ICD nomenclature, must be entered at the time of the admission examination. The final diagnosis may differ if subsequent evaluation supports a change. If a diagnosis is absent, justification must be documented. Intercurrent (non-psychiatric) diagnoses must be documented when made. Attention should be paid to physical examination notes, known medical conditions, allergies, recent exposure to infections or substance abuse, and laboratory or test reports identifying abnormal findings."},{"type":"probe","text":"Probes §482.61(a)(2)"},{"type":"q","text":"Are abnormal physical examination findings and/or laboratory findings justified by further diagnostic testing and/or development of an intercurrent diagnosis, and if so, was such done?"},{"type":"q","text":"If an identified physical illness requires immediate treatment, is the treatment being given?"},{"type":"q","text":"How will an identified physical illness be likely to impact on the patient's eventual outcome? To what extent has this potential impact been addressed by the team?"},{"type":"para","text":"(a)(3) Reasons for Admission"},{"type":"p","text":"The record must document—preferably verbatim—statements and reasons for admission given by the patient, family, and others, with the informant identified. Records must not contain vague, ill-defined reports from unknown sources; they must record 'who,' 'what,' 'where,' 'when,' and 'why.'"},{"type":"probe","text":"Probes §482.61(a)(3)"},{"type":"q","text":"Can the patient describe problems, stresses, situations experienced prior to hospitalization, or do they still exist?"},{"type":"q","text":"Who is the informant? Did the informant witness the patient's behavior? If not, on what basis has the informant come to know the patient's behavior?"},{"type":"q","text":"Has staff elicited whether the patient has exhibited similar behavior previously? If so, what was different this time to make hospitalization necessary?"},{"type":"q","text":"Were there other changes/events in the patient's environment (death, separations of significant others) which contributed to the need for hospitalization? If so, has staff explored how these will impact the patient's treatment?"},{"type":"q","text":"Has there been an interruption or change in the patient's medication which may have been a factor in the patient's hospitalization?"},{"type":"para","text":"(a)(4) Social Service Records"},{"type":"p","text":"A psychosocial history/assessment must be completed on all patients. Three key components must be addressed: (A) Factual and Historical Information — specific reasons for admission or readmission, description of past and present biopsychosocial functioning, family and marital history and dynamics, pertinent religious and cultural factors, history of physical/sexual/emotional abuse, significant aspects of psychiatric/medical/substance abuse history, educational/vocational/employment/military service history, identification of community resources, identification of present environmental and financial needs; (B) Social Evaluation — patient strengths and deficits, high-risk psychosocial issues requiring early treatment planning; (C) Conclusions and Recommendations — anticipated necessary steps for discharge, high-risk issues requiring early intervention, specific community resources/support systems, anticipated social work role(s) in treatment and discharge planning."},{"type":"probe","text":"Probes §482.61(a)(4)"},{"type":"q","text":"Does the psychosocial history/assessment clearly identify the informant(s) and sources of information?"},{"type":"q","text":"Does it indicate whether information is considered reliable?"},{"type":"q","text":"Does it indicate patient participation to the extent possible in provision of data relative to treatment and discharge planning?"},{"type":"q","text":"Does it integrate significant data including identified high-risk psychosocial issues (problems) into the treatment plan?"},{"type":"q","text":"How does the hospital ensure the information is reliable?"},{"type":"para","text":"(a)(5) Neurological Examination"},{"type":"p","text":"When indicated, a complete neurological examination must be recorded at the time of the admission physical examination. A 'screening' neurological exam assesses gross function of the various divisions of the central nervous system; statements such as 'Cranial Nerves II–XII intact' alone are not acceptable. If positive neurological symptomatology is found, a more detailed examination must be ordered. A complete, comprehensive neurological examination is a detailed, orderly survey of all sections of the nervous system, requiring a physician who reviews the patient's full history and psychiatric evaluation."},{"type":"probe","text":"Probes §482.61(a)(5)"},{"type":"q","text":"Did the presence of an abnormal physical finding or laboratory finding justify the need for further diagnostic testing, or for the development of an intercurrent diagnosis? If the finding justified further follow-up, was such follow-up done?"},{"type":"q","text":"Is there evidence that a screening neurological examination was done and recorded at the time of the physical examination?"},{"type":"q","text":"Was the screening neurological or history indicative of possible involvement (tremors, paralysis, motor weakness or muscle atrophy, severe headaches, seizures, head trauma)?"},{"type":"q","text":"If indicated, was a complete, comprehensive neurological exam ordered, completed, and recorded in the medical record in a timely manner?"},{"type":"std","text":"§ 482.61(b) — Psychiatric Evaluation (B110–B117)"},{"type":"p","text":"The psychiatric evaluation is a total appraisal of the patient's illness performed to determine diagnosis and treatment. It must contain sufficient information to justify the diagnosis and planned treatment, and must include a biographical-historical perspective of the patient's personality as a specific human being. A physician signature is required; where a non-physician performs the mental status portion, they must be credentialed by the hospital, legally authorized by the State, and physician countersignature must be present where required by policy or State law."},{"type":"p","text":"The psychiatric evaluation should include: the patient's chief complaints/reaction to hospitalization (in patient's own words); past history of psychiatric problems and treatment; past family, educational, vocational, occupational and social history; and all information necessary to justify the diagnosis and treatment."},{"type":"probe","text":"Probes §482.61(b) — General"},{"type":"q","text":"Why is the patient in the hospital? Was it his/her idea? Is the patient in the hospital against his/her will? Who decided to hospitalize and why?"},{"type":"q","text":"Has the patient been chronically ill? Continuously/repeatedly? How severely has past illness/treatment interfered with the patient's development and/or adjustment?"},{"type":"q","text":"Are there persistent symptoms/signs/behaviors that must be addressed and treated in order to favorably impact the future psychiatric course?"},{"type":"q","text":"What medications or supports helped the patient improve in the past? Are the same resources available for this episode?"},{"type":"q","text":"What is the patient's educational level? What jobs has the patient held? How does the patient get along with people?"},{"type":"q","text":"Within the psychiatric evaluation, do one find the specific signs and symptoms, and other factors, that justify the diagnosis?"},{"type":"para","text":"(b)(1) Timing"},{"type":"p","text":"Must be completed within 60 hours of admission."},{"type":"para","text":"(b)(2) Medical History"},{"type":"p","text":"Must include the non-psychiatric medical history including physical disabilities, intellectual disabilities, and treatment."},{"type":"probe","text":"Probes §482.61(b)(2)"},{"type":"q","text":"Does the evaluation include relevant past surgery and past medical conditions and disabilities, especially those of a chronic nature?"},{"type":"q","text":"Have these conditions contributed to the patient's psychiatric condition? How?"},{"type":"q","text":"Are any of these conditions still present to a significant degree? Are they likely to impact the patient's recovery/remission? Should they be addressed immediately? Does the facility have the capability to intervene?"},{"type":"para","text":"(b)(3) Mental Status"},{"type":"p","text":"Must describe the appearance and behavior, emotional response, verbalization, thought content, and cognition of the patient as reported by the patient and observed by the examiner at the time of the examination. Simply stating conclusions (e.g., 'oriented, memory intact, judgment poor, insight nil') without supporting clinical narrative is not acceptable."},{"type":"para","text":"(b)(4) Onset of Illness"},{"type":"p","text":"Must include history of present illness: onset, precipitating factors, reason for current admission, signs and symptoms, course, and results of any treatment received."},{"type":"probe","text":"Probes §482.61(b)(4)"},{"type":"q","text":"How long has the patient been ill? Was it a gradual or sudden onset? Is this a recurrence?"},{"type":"q","text":"What were the precipitating factors? What happened?"},{"type":"q","text":"What symptoms, signs, behaviors made this hospitalization necessary?"},{"type":"q","text":"What treatment has the patient already received before coming to the hospital? Is any medication received listed?"},{"type":"para","text":"(b)(5) Attitudes and Behavior"},{"type":"p","text":"The problem statement should describe behaviors requiring change for the patient to function in a less restrictive setting, including behavioral or relationship difficulties with significant others requiring active treatment to facilitate successful discharge."},{"type":"para","text":"(b)(6) Intellectual Functioning, Memory, and Orientation"},{"type":"p","text":"Refer to guidance for § 482.61(b)(3). These elements must be substantiated with clinical narrative, not just conclusory labels."},{"type":"para","text":"(b)(7) Inventory of Patient Assets"},{"type":"p","text":"Assets must be described in descriptive, not interpretive fashion. Only personal factors usable in therapy qualify as 'strengths'—knowledge, interests, skills, aptitudes, personal experiences, education, talents, and employment status. Words such as 'youth,' 'pretty,' 'Social Security income,' and 'has a car' do not represent assets."},{"type":"std","text":"§ 482.61(c) — Treatment Plan (B118–B125)"},{"type":"p","text":"The patient and treatment team collaboratively develop the treatment plan—the outline of what the hospital has committed to do for the patient, based on assessment of needs. There must be evidence of periodic review of the patient's response and progress; if progress is made or lacking, the review must justify continuing current goals or revising the plan. The interval for treatment plan reviews is determined by the hospital, but must be sufficiently responsive to ensure review whenever: a goal is accomplished; the patient is regressing; the patient is failing to progress; or a new treatment goal is required."},{"type":"sp","text":"Survey Procedure §482.61(c)(1) — Compliance Determination Method"},{"type":"sp_p","text":"1. Observation of patient and staff at planned therapies/meetings, in formal and informal settings on and off units."},{"type":"sp_p","text":"2. Interviews with patients, families, treatment staff, and others involved in active treatment."},{"type":"sp_p","text":"3. Review of scheduled treatment programs (individual, group, family meetings, therapeutic activities, therapeutic procedures)."},{"type":"sp_p","text":"4. Attendance at multidisciplinary treatment planning meetings, if time permits."},{"type":"sp_p","text":"5. Medical record review."},{"type":"probe","text":"Probe §482.61(c)(1)"},{"type":"q","text":"Has the information gained from assessing/evaluating the patient been utilized to create an individualized treatment plan?"},{"type":"para","text":"(c)(1) Plan Must Be Based on Strengths and Disabilities"},{"type":"p","text":"'Disability' means any psychiatric or biopsychosocial problem requiring treatment/intervention (used interchangeably with 'problem'). The treatment plan is derived from the psychiatric evaluation and assessments/diagnostic data collected by the total treatment team. Patient strengths that can be utilized in treatment must be identified. Treatment planning depends on whether the admission is for crisis intervention, short-term treatment, or long-term treatment."},{"type":"probe","text":"Probes §482.61(c)(1) — Strengths and Disabilities"},{"type":"q","text":"Is the treatment plan individualized (patient-specific), or is there a predictable sameness from plan to plan?"},{"type":"q","text":"When packaged plans or programs are used, do staff include needed individual adaptations in the plan?"},{"type":"q","text":"Are the patient's observed behaviors consistent with the problems and strengths identified in the plan or update?"},{"type":"q","text":"Have the views which the patient communicated to the surveyor regarding problems requiring treatment and plans for discharge been incorporated in the plan or update?"},{"type":"para","text":"(c)(1)(i) Substantiated Diagnosis"},{"type":"p","text":"The substantiated diagnosis is the diagnosis identified by the treatment team to be the primary focus for treatment planning. It evolves from synthesis of data from various disciplines. Rule-out diagnoses alone are not acceptable as a substantiated diagnosis. At the time of treatment planning, a substantiated diagnosis must be recorded; it may be the same as or different from the initial diagnosis."},{"type":"probe","text":"Probes §482.61(c)(1)(i)"},{"type":"q","text":"What specific problems will be treated during the patient's hospitalization?"},{"type":"q","text":"Does the treatment plan identify and precisely describe problem behaviors rather than generalized statements (i.e., 'paranoid,' 'aggressive,' 'depressed') or generic terminology (i.e., 'alteration in thought process,' 'ineffective coping')?"},{"type":"q","text":"Are physical problems identified and included in the treatment plan if they require treatment or interfere with treatment during hospitalization?"},{"type":"para","text":"(c)(1)(ii) Short-Term and Long-Range Goals"},{"type":"p","text":"Goals must include specific dates for expected achievement, be stated as observable and measurable patient behaviors, and be related to identified problems. The long-range goal is achieved through a series of short-term goals. As goals are achieved, the treatment plan should be revised. In crisis/short-term stays, there may be only one timeframe."},{"type":"probe","text":"Probes §482.61(c)(1)(ii)"},{"type":"q","text":"How do treatment plan goals relate to the problems being treated?"},{"type":"q","text":"Do goals indicate the outcomes to be achieved by the patient?"},{"type":"q","text":"Are the goals written in a way that allows changes in the patient's behavior to be measured?"},{"type":"q","text":"If not apparent, what criteria do staff use to measure success?"},{"type":"q","text":"How relevant are the treatment plan goals to the patient's condition?"},{"type":"para","text":"(c)(1)(iii) Specific Treatment Modalities"},{"type":"p","text":"All planned treatment modalities must be identified. Simply 'naming' modalities (e.g., 'individual therapy, group therapy, occupational therapy') is not acceptable—the focus of the treatment must be included. Simply 'stating' generic approaches (e.g., 'set limits,' 'encourage socialization') is not acceptable; approaches must be specifically described. A daily schedule of unit activities does not in itself constitute planned modalities."},{"type":"probe","text":"Probes §482.61(c)(1)(iii)"},{"type":"q","text":"Are qualified staff observed following the methods, approaches, and staff interventions as stated?"},{"type":"q","text":"Can staff explain the focus of the modality they have provided?"},{"type":"q","text":"Are observed treatment methods, approaches, and interventions from all disciplines included in the plan?"},{"type":"q","text":"Do the pieces of the treatment plan work together to achieve the greatest possible gain for the patient?"},{"type":"q","text":"Do the disciplines present at observed treatment planning meetings represent all of the patient's needs?"},{"type":"q","text":"Is the patient included in the decision-making whenever possible?"},{"type":"q","text":"How does the patient get to know his/her treatment regime?"},{"type":"para","text":"(c)(1)(iv) Responsibilities of Each Team Member"},{"type":"p","text":"Each individual on the treatment team primarily responsible for ensuring compliance with particular aspects of the patient's individualized treatment program must be identified by name and discipline. The patient, as well as family/significant others, should be aware of the staff responsible for various aspects of treatment."},{"type":"probe","text":"Probes §482.61(c)(1)(iv)"},{"type":"q","text":"Are staff who are designated in the treatment plan observed carrying out treatment activities and therapies? Is the information in the plan consistent with surveyor observations?"},{"type":"q","text":"Are the patients able to name the staff responsible for implementing their treatment? Is this information consistent with the treatment plan?"},{"type":"para","text":"(c)(1)(v) Adequate Documentation"},{"type":"p","text":"When progress and treatment notes are reviewed, the content of the notes must relate to the treatment plan, indicating what hospital staff is doing to carry out the treatment plan and the patient's response to the interventions."},{"type":"probe","text":"Probes §482.61(c)(1)(v)"},{"type":"q","text":"Are the treatment notes relative to the identified problems?"},{"type":"q","text":"Are the treatment notes indicative of the patient's response to treatment?"},{"type":"q","text":"Do the progress notes relate to specific patient problems or progress?"},{"type":"para","text":"(c)(2) Active Treatment Documentation"},{"type":"p","text":"Active treatment is a clinical process involving ongoing assessment, diagnosis, intervention, evaluation, and discharge planning under the direction of a psychiatrist. The record must indicate adherence to the patient's right to be counseled about medication (intended effects and potential side effects). Treatment notes document provision of and patient response to a specific modality. Progress notes give a chronological picture of progress toward treatment plan goals. A combined treatment and progress note may be written."},{"type":"probe","text":"Probes §482.61(c)(2)"},{"type":"q","text":"Does the patient know his/her diagnosis?"},{"type":"q","text":"What did the patient contribute to the formulation of the treatment plan? Goals of treatment?"},{"type":"q","text":"If the patient receives medication, does the patient understand the reason for the medication, the name, the dose, the time of administration, the desired effects, and the potential side effects?"},{"type":"q","text":"If medication is changed, is there a rationale for the change?"},{"type":"q","text":"Are staff members recording their observations relative to the patient's response to the treatment modalities, including medication?"},{"type":"q","text":"Is there evidence that the patient was afforded the opportunity to participate in his/her plan of care?"},{"type":"q","text":"What progress has the patient made? Has the patient achieved his/her optimal level of functioning? If not, why? Are these reasons/barriers reflected in the current treatment plan?"},{"type":"q","text":"If a restrictive procedure is used (e.g., restraint and/or seclusion), is there evidence that attempts were made systematically to treat the patient in the least restrictive manner?"},{"type":"q","text":"Is there evidence that the rights of the patient were protected while in the restrictive setting in accordance with Federal and State law and accepted standards of practice?"},{"type":"std","text":"§ 482.61(d) — Recording Progress (B126–B132)"},{"type":"p","text":"Progress notes must give a chronological picture of the patient's progress or lack of progress toward attaining short- and long-range goals. Notes stating 'patient slept well' or 'no complaints' constitute observations only and do not indicate how the patient is responding to treatment. Frequency alone does not determine adequacy—expect greater frequency when patients are more acutely ill or in crisis. Notes must be dated and signed with signature and title or discipline."},{"type":"p","text":"Required note authors: (1) the MD/DO responsible for the patient's care; (2) nurse; (3) social worker; (4) when appropriate, others significantly involved in active treatment modalities."},{"type":"p","text":"Minimum frequency: at least weekly for the first 2 months, at least once a month thereafter."},{"type":"p","text":"Notes must contain: (1) recommendations for revisions in the treatment plan as indicated; (2) a precise assessment of the patient's progress in accordance with the original or revised treatment plan."},{"type":"probe","text":"Probes §482.61(d)"},{"type":"q","text":"Are the physicians who are significantly involved in active treatment modalities/interventions actually documenting progress?"},{"type":"q","text":"Are the nurses who are significantly involved in active treatment modalities/interventions actually documenting progress?"},{"type":"q","text":"Are the social workers significantly involved in active treatment modalities/interventions actually documenting progress?"},{"type":"q","text":"Are staff from other disciplines (e.g., rehabilitative therapy and psychology) which are significantly involved in active treatment modalities/interventions actually documenting progress?"},{"type":"q","text":"Do the progress notes relate to the goals of the treatment plan? Do they include precise statements of progress?"},{"type":"q","text":"Is there a correlation between what is observed by the surveyor and what is described in the notes?"},{"type":"q","text":"Do the notes give a clear picture of the patient's progress or lack thereof during the course of hospitalization?"},{"type":"q","text":"In reviewing the patient's progress, are aftercare/discharge plans being evaluated?"},{"type":"q","text":"Do the progress notes contain documentation substantiating changes/revisions in the treatment plan and subsequent assessment of the patient's responses and progress?"},{"type":"std","text":"§ 482.61(e) — Discharge Planning and Discharge Summary (B133–B135)"},{"type":"p","text":"The discharge summary must contain: (1) a recapitulation of the patient's hospitalization—summary of circumstances and rationale for admission, synopsis of accomplishments as reflected through the treatment plan, reasons for admission, treatment achieved, baseline of psychiatric/physical/social functioning at discharge, evidence of patient/family response to interventions; (2) recommendations from appropriate services concerning follow-up or aftercare; (3) a brief summary of the patient's condition on discharge."},{"type":"p","text":"Aftercare recommendations must describe services and supports effective on the day of discharge, including: complete description of arrangements with treatment and community resources for follow-up services; a plan outlining psychiatric/medical treatment and medication regimen; specific appointment date(s) and names and addresses of service provider(s); description of community housing/living arrangement; economic/financial status or plan; recreational and leisure resources; and a complete description of the involvement of family and significant others post-discharge."},{"type":"probe","text":"Probes §482.61(e)"},{"type":"q","text":"How does the discharge planning process verify appointment source(s), dates, and addresses?"},{"type":"q","text":"How was the patient involved in the discharge and aftercare planning process?"},{"type":"q","text":"Were discharge-related documents made available to the patient, family, community treatment source, and/or other appropriate sources?"},{"type":"q","text":"Is there indication that the discharge planning process included participation of multidisciplinary staff and the patient? Have the results been communicated to the post-hospital treatment entity?"},{"type":"q","text":"Is there evidence that contact with the post-hospital treatment entity included communication of treatment recommendations (including information regarding the patient's medications)?"},{"type":"q","text":"Is a contact person named, and does the patient have a specific appointment date and time for the initial follow-up visit?"}]},{"id":"ig-482-62","citation":"§ 482.62","title":"Special Staff Requirements","tag":"psych","source":"SOM Appendix AA","link":"https://www.cms.gov/regulations-and-guidance/guidance/manuals/downloads/som107ap_aa_psyc_hospitals.pdf","body":[{"type":"std","text":"B136 | Condition-Level Guidance"},{"type":"p","text":"The purpose of this CoP is to ensure the psychiatric hospital is adequately staffed with qualified mental health professionals and supportive staff to carry out an intensive and comprehensive active treatment program and to protect and promote the physical and mental health of patients. 'Adequate numbers' means the numbers and deployment of staff with qualifications to evaluate, plan, implement, and document active treatment—not numbers alone."},{"type":"sp","text":"Survey Procedure §482.62 — Assessment Method"},{"type":"sp_p","text":"1. Observe sampled patients and others during structured sessions and in unstructured settings for behavioral evidence of a rational organization of resources."},{"type":"sp_p","text":"2. Interview patients and staff to determine whether necessary treatment modalities and services are being provided in a timely manner."},{"type":"sp_p","text":"3. Review medical records of patients in the sample to ascertain if active treatment assessments, treatments, evaluations, and activities have been conducted and documented."},{"type":"sp_p","text":"4. Review other records such as restraint and seclusion records, incident reports, medication error reports, patient/staff injury reports to determine the extent to which staffing levels or deployment contributed to negative patient outcomes."},{"type":"sp_p","text":"5. Evaluate all outcome data in light of the success or failure observed during the survey relevant to each patient receiving active treatment. This is the primary basis for evaluating the adequacy of staffing under this Special Condition."},{"type":"std","text":"§ 482.62(a) — Personnel (B137–B140)"},{"type":"para","text":"(a)(1) Evaluate Patients"},{"type":"p","text":"Staff must be sufficient to assure that the admission work-ups (assessment, diagnostic data gathering) are completed in a timely manner, and that continuing evaluation of the patient's progress and response to treatment is occurring."},{"type":"probe","text":"Probes §482.62(a)(1)"},{"type":"q","text":"Is there adequate staff to assure that admission work-ups are completed in a timely manner?"},{"type":"q","text":"Is there evidence that there is continuing evaluation of the patient's progress and response to treatment?"},{"type":"q","text":"Are evaluations delayed or absent?"},{"type":"para","text":"(a)(2) Formulate Written Individualized, Comprehensive Treatment Plans"},{"type":"p","text":"Staffing must be sufficient so that members of the patient's treatment team and others responsible for evaluation and assessment can contribute their respective data for consideration in the formulation of the treatment plan."},{"type":"probe","text":"Probes §482.62(a)(2)"},{"type":"q","text":"Was there sufficient discipline participation at the treatment team meeting to assure formulation of a treatment plan that meets the patient's individualized needs?"},{"type":"q","text":"What problems prevent staff members from attending treatment meetings? Do they relate to staffing?"},{"type":"q","text":"Are the assessments/evaluations absent or delayed to the extent that they are not useful to the treatment team for the purpose of planning individualized treatment?"},{"type":"para","text":"(a)(3) Provide Active Treatment Measures"},{"type":"p","text":"Active treatment occurs when the patient receives treatment interventions delivered under physician direction, specific to patient strengths, disabilities, and problems identified in the treatment plan, in accordance with accepted standards. Treatment must be individualized—several patients may attend the same group, but the focus of discussion and therapeutic intervention may differ depending on the individual patient's particular issue. Expect to see treatment focused on the unique needs of individual patients."},{"type":"probe","text":"Probes §482.62(a)(3)"},{"type":"q","text":"Through observation, interviews, and record reviews, can you determine that patients receive active treatment?"},{"type":"q","text":"Is the distribution of staff consistent with particular patient needs? Is appropriate staffing sufficient to carry out treatment plans?"},{"type":"q","text":"Does the patient attend therapies that are relevant to the identified problems that brought the patient to the hospital?"},{"type":"q","text":"Are staff absences and/or vacancies preventing the patient from receiving active treatment? Are patients not attending therapeutic activities off the unit because there is no staff to escort them?"},{"type":"q","text":"Are patients observed not engaged in activities while staff attend to administrative tasks?"},{"type":"q","text":"Are active treatment sessions or activities carried out at discrete time intervals exclusively, or is active treatment implemented as the patient's needs emerge during the course of the day as well?"},{"type":"q","text":"Does a review of quality assurance data reveal a pattern of serious incidents occurring on particular shifts and/or days of the week?"},{"type":"q","text":"What do patients report to the surveyor are their treatment modalities? Do patient interviews indicate that patients believe the treatment being provided is helpful?"},{"type":"q","text":"Does the scheduling of activities and their content relate directly to the patient's treatment objectives, or are the activities/content generalized, non-therapeutic 'time-fillers'?"},{"type":"q","text":"Is there a consistent, observable pattern of evidence that hospital staff provide, reinforce, and otherwise implement measures to achieve active treatment objectives?"},{"type":"para","text":"(a)(4) Engage in Discharge Planning"},{"type":"p","text":"The patient together with all relevant professionals caring for the patient should be expected to participate in the discharge planning process. Staffing should be sufficient to facilitate this outcome to the maximum extent possible."},{"type":"probe","text":"Probes §482.62(a)(4)"},{"type":"q","text":"Do patients participate in their discharge planning process? If not, why?"},{"type":"q","text":"Do staff interviews elicit information that staff working with patients are aware of the discharge plans for those patients?"},{"type":"q","text":"Do record review and interviews indicate that all relevant staff have participated in discharge planning?"},{"type":"std","text":"§ 482.62(b) — Director of Inpatient Psychiatric Services; Medical Staff (B141–B144)"},{"type":"p","text":"Inpatient psychiatric services must be under the supervision of a clinical director, service chief, or equivalent qualified to provide leadership for an intensive treatment program. The clinical director is ultimately responsible for medical and psychiatric care provided to patients, must ensure quality improvement programs monitor all areas of patient care, and must implement educational programs for all staff levels. Inpatient psychiatric services include: admission interviews, assessments, psychiatric and medical work-ups, treatment team leadership, medication management, on-call emergency treatment, individual/group/family therapies, clinical supervision, and educational conferences."},{"type":"sp","text":"Survey Procedure §482.62(b) — Meeting with Clinical Director"},{"type":"sp_p","text":"Just prior to the end of the survey, schedule a meeting with the clinical director. By this time you should have conducted required observations, interviews, and record reviews for at least a majority of sampled patients. Collect information regarding: the qualifications of the clinical director; the leadership exhibited for the scope of psychiatric/medical treatment programs needed by patients; and the rationale for medical staffing coverage."},{"type":"para","text":"(b)(1) Qualifications of Clinical Director"},{"type":"p","text":"Must meet training and experience requirements for examination by the American Board of Psychiatry and Neurology (ABPN) or the American Osteopathic Board of Neurology and Psychiatry. This requires: unrestricted license; graduation from AMA- or AOA-approved medical school; successful completion of an approved psychiatric residency (≥3 years before 1988; ≥4 years after 1988). Actual board certification satisfies this requirement; evidence of eligibility for the board examination also satisfies it."},{"type":"sp","text":"Survey Procedure §482.62(b)(1) — Credential Review"},{"type":"sp_p","text":"Review the clinical director's personnel folder or ask whether he/she has: (a) certification of the ABPN and/or American Osteopathic Board of Neurology and Psychiatry; (b) if not certified, evidence that the person took the Boards (would satisfy training and equivalency); or (c) medical school and residency training documentation."},{"type":"para","text":"(b)(2) Quality Monitoring by Director"},{"type":"p","text":"The director must monitor and evaluate the quality and appropriateness of services and treatment provided by the medical staff, in accordance with acceptable standards of practice. In states where psychologists have admitting privileges, the clinical director retains oversight responsibility."},{"type":"probe","text":"Probes §482.62(b)(2)"},{"type":"q","text":"What mechanisms does the director use to monitor and evaluate the work of the medical staff (personal interviews, Quality Improvement reports, incident reports)?"},{"type":"q","text":"When problems are discovered by the clinical director, how are they corrected?"},{"type":"q","text":"Are services, notes, and reports timely?"},{"type":"q","text":"Are medications used appropriately for the patient's diagnosis?"},{"type":"para","text":"(b) Adequacy of Medical Staff"},{"type":"p","text":"The number and qualifications of MD/DOs must be adequate to provide essential psychiatric services, considering: (1) number of admissions, discharges, and current patients by treatment unit; (2) size of the hospital; (3) geographic proximity of the wards and units; (4) organization and kinds of treatment services rendered; (5) availability of physician coverage on evenings, nights, and weekends; (6) availability of physicians for treatment planning; (7) availability of psychiatrists to consult with non-psychiatric physicians about psychotropic medication regimens; (8) availability of physicians to consult with multi-disciplinary staff about treatment issues."},{"type":"probe","text":"Probes §482.62(b) — Medical Staff"},{"type":"q","text":"How many staff are board certified? Fully trained? How many full-time/part-time specialties are represented?"},{"type":"q","text":"How are medical staff deployed? To what programs/units are they assigned? Why?"},{"type":"q","text":"How much time do physicians spend on the units? Based on observations, interviews, and medical record reviews, is coverage adequate to meet the needs of sampled patients?"},{"type":"std","text":"§ 482.62(c) — Availability of Medical Personnel (B145)"},{"type":"p","text":"MD/DOs and other appropriate professional personnel must be available to provide necessary medical and surgical diagnostic and treatment services. If not available within the institution, there must be an agreement with an outside source for immediate availability, or a satisfactory arrangement for transferring patients to a Medicare-participating general hospital."},{"type":"probe","text":"Probes §482.62(c)"},{"type":"q","text":"How did the hospital meet the medical/surgical/diagnostic needs represented by each patient in the sample? Were these done timely? Appropriately?"},{"type":"q","text":"If contracts are not current or available, how are these services provided for the patient? Is there evidence of negative outcomes as a result of these arrangements?"},{"type":"q","text":"Are reports from other services such as pharmacy, radiology, and clinical laboratory timely? Appropriate?"},{"type":"std","text":"§ 482.62(d) — Nursing Services (B146–B150)"},{"type":"p","text":"Psychiatric nursing functions include: supervision of paraprofessional staff; assessment, planning, provision, and evaluation of psychiatric nursing care; medication teaching; management of the therapeutic milieu; mandatory and voluntary in-service training; and provision of specialized treatments requiring clinical expertise of a professional psychiatric nurse. Expect to see evidence of orientation programs and ongoing continuing education for LPNs and mental health workers emphasizing individualized treatment interventions."},{"type":"para","text":"(d)(1) Director of Psychiatric Nursing Services"},{"type":"p","text":"Must be an RN with a master's degree in psychiatric or mental health nursing from an NLN-accredited school, or be qualified by education and experience in care of the mentally ill. If the DON has less than a master's degree in psychiatric nursing, expect to see evidence of ongoing training; documented consultation from a master's-prepared psychiatric nurse constitutes ongoing training. The DON must demonstrate competence in interdisciplinary treatment plan formulation, skilled nursing care and therapy, and direction, monitoring, and evaluation of nursing care."},{"type":"probe","text":"Probes §482.62(d)(1)"},{"type":"q","text":"Are nursing assessments completed on all patients?"},{"type":"q","text":"Do the multidisciplinary treatment plans reflect nursing input including specific nursing interventions for nursing problems (e.g., violence toward self/others, physical/medical crises)?"},{"type":"q","text":"Is nursing care evaluated by an RN, with changes in care based on the patient's progress or lack thereof?"},{"type":"q","text":"Are intrusive techniques (e.g., seclusion, restraint, ECT, and/or medical procedures) and patient incidents (e.g., medication errors, patient falls, patient-to-patient and patient-to-staff injuries) monitored in accordance with hospital policy, State statutes, and safe nursing practice?"},{"type":"q","text":"Are nursing personnel observed relating to patients in a therapeutic manner?"},{"type":"para","text":"(d)(2) Staffing Requirements"},{"type":"p","text":"A registered nurse must be available 24 hours each day. Adequate numbers of RNs, LPNs, and mental health workers must be available to provide the nursing care necessary under each patient's active treatment program. Evaluation of sufficiency considers patient characteristics from observations, interviews, and medical records. Mental health workers must have education, experience, and/or training in psychiatric care and must be assigned duties reflecting their educational level and psychiatric training."},{"type":"sp","text":"Survey Procedure §482.62(d)(2) — Staffing Review"},{"type":"sp_p","text":"Review nursing staffing patterns on a sample of approximately 25% of certified wards. Review staffing for the day(s) of the survey and evaluate based on patient needs. If a problem or concern is evidenced, review additional data."},{"type":"sp_p","text":"If observations and/or interviews indicate a staffing problem, consider the following variables: organization and types of services provided by nursing; number and levels of nursing care needs including average length of stay and acuity; number and levels of nursing personnel based on roles and functions required; number of suicidal/assaultive patients; seclusion/restraint incidents; number of admissions and discharges; number and type of accidents and/or injuries; amount and complexity of medication regimens; medication errors; use of PRN medications; medical (physical) procedures; assignment and utilization of pool nursing personnel; availability of RNs to supervise/consult with nursing/non-nursing personnel; availability of RNs to assess and implement care in crisis situations; and involvement of patients with personnel."},{"type":"probe","text":"Probes §482.62(d)(2)"},{"type":"q","text":"Are personnel interacting with patients? Are patients involved in structured activities?"},{"type":"q","text":"Are patients lying in beds/on floors, sitting alone, fighting and arguing?"},{"type":"q","text":"When interviewing/observing staff, do they interact therapeutically with patients?"},{"type":"q","text":"Why have nursing staff been deployed in the manner that they have?"},{"type":"std","text":"§ 482.62(e) — Psychological Services (B151)"},{"type":"p","text":"The hospital must provide or have available psychological services to meet patient needs. Services may include: diagnostic testing and diagnostic formulations on physician request; individual, group, and family therapies; participation in multidisciplinary treatment conferences; and program development and evaluation. The number of full-time, part-time, and consulting psychologists must be adequate; arrangements with outside resources must assure necessary patient services will be provided."},{"type":"probe","text":"Probes §482.62(e)"},{"type":"q","text":"Did the patients in the sample have a need for psychological services or testing? Were they provided in a timely manner and with sufficient intensity?"},{"type":"q","text":"Did any of the patients in the sample indicate a need for psychological services, but none were requested?"},{"type":"q","text":"What types of psychological services are offered (e.g., assessments, therapy)?"},{"type":"q","text":"Do certain groups of patients receive testing routinely (dementia, children, adolescents)? Why?"},{"type":"q","text":"Once tests are performed, are results reported in sufficient time to be integrated into the patient's active treatment and treatment plan?"},{"type":"q","text":"How does the hospital or Psychological Service Department determine whether it meets the needs of patients? Whether its services are underutilized or over-utilized?"},{"type":"q","text":"Why have psychological services staff been deployed in the manner that they have?"},{"type":"std","text":"§ 482.62(f) — Social Services (B152–B155)"},{"type":"p","text":"Social work functions include: intake/admission screening; psychosocial assessment; developing an update or detailed re-assessment; high-social risk case finding; contact with family and significant others; patient and family education, support, and advocacy; coordination/liaison with community-based agencies; participation as a treatment team member; provision of supportive/individual/couple/family/group therapy; case management; and post-discharge follow-up. Continuity of care is a key social work principle. When non-social workers perform these duties, the Director of Social Work or an MSW-qualified supervisor must be involved to oversee quality."},{"type":"sp","text":"Survey Procedure §482.62(f) — Meeting with Director of Social Work"},{"type":"sp_p","text":"Just prior to the end of the survey, schedule a meeting with the Director of Social Work. By this time you should have conducted required observations, interviews, and record reviews for at least a majority of sampled patients. Collect information regarding: the qualifications of the director; the leadership exhibited for the scope of services needed by the patient; and the rationale for social work staffing coverage."},{"type":"probe","text":"Probes §482.62(f)"},{"type":"q","text":"How does the director periodically audit the quality of social work services furnished?"},{"type":"q","text":"What are the outcomes of audits conducted? What percentage of psychosocial assessments was completed and available in written form at the time of the interdisciplinary treatment plan?"},{"type":"q","text":"How does the patient's social needs as addressed by the social worker in the psychosocial assessment compare against the goals developed in the interdisciplinary treatment plan?"},{"type":"q","text":"Has social work staff provided active treatment in accordance with the patient's treatment plan?"},{"type":"para","text":"(f)(1) Director Qualifications"},{"type":"p","text":"Must have a master's degree from an accredited school of social work, or be qualified by education and experience in the social services needs of the mentally ill. If the director does not hold an MSW, at least one staff member must have this qualification. Duties and responsibilities must be clearly delineated in facility policies and procedures."},{"type":"probe","text":"Probes §482.62(f)(1)"},{"type":"q","text":"What are the director's qualifications, experience, and scope of duties within this position?"},{"type":"q","text":"If a MSW staff member other than the director is performing any of these duties, what are this staff member's experience and scope of duties performed? Why were these duties delegated?"},{"type":"q","text":"To what extent is the director knowledgeable of the social work needs of the various wards?"},{"type":"q","text":"Why has the social work staff and services provided throughout the hospital been deployed in the manner they have?"},{"type":"para","text":"(f)(2) Staff Responsibilities"},{"type":"p","text":"Social work contact with the patient, family, and significant others should occur during or as soon as possible after admission. High-risk case finding should result in significant data being available for early integration into the treatment plan. Social work staff responsibilities must include: participating in discharge planning; arranging for follow-up care; and developing mechanisms for exchange of appropriate information with sources outside the hospital."},{"type":"probe","text":"Probes §482.62(f)(2)"},{"type":"q","text":"Are social work staff routinely involved in providing services to the patient that are identified in the treatment plan?"},{"type":"q","text":"To what extent do social work staff provide discharge planning services to the patient, such as supportive therapy focused on discharge goals, and carrying out a liaison role with community resource providers?"},{"type":"q","text":"Have social work staff assured that adequate information is provided to post-hospital patient service providers?"},{"type":"std","text":"§ 482.62(g) — Therapeutic Activities (B156–B158)"},{"type":"p","text":"A variety of therapeutic and rehabilitative activities are selectively used as therapeutic tools in providing active treatment. Therapeutic activities focus on development and maintenance of adaptive skills to improve patient functioning. Leisure activities provide individualized opportunities to acquire knowledge, skills, and attitudes about meaningful leisure involvement. Rehabilitative services may include educational, occupational, recreational, physical, art, dance, music, and speech therapies, and vocational rehabilitation."},{"type":"para","text":"(g)(1) Program Appropriateness"},{"type":"p","text":"The program must be appropriate to patient needs and interests, directed toward restoring and maintaining optimal physical and psychosocial functioning. The hospital is responsible for ensuring consistent availability and provision of individualized therapeutic activities and rehabilitative services based on patient needs. Selection of modalities must be based on patient need and goals set in the patient's treatment plan."},{"type":"probe","text":"Probes §482.62(g)(1)"},{"type":"q","text":"Are activity areas/sites accessible and available to meet the patient's individual needs? Are the facilities and resources adequate to enable implementation of goals set in the treatment plan?"},{"type":"q","text":"Does the program utilize available community resources to provide opportunities for socialization, leisure, and therapeutic activities for patients who can participate outside the hospital setting?"},{"type":"q","text":"Are current activity schedules clearly posted for patient and staff reference and use? Are the scheduled activities related to the particular patient area and specific treatment needs of patients?"},{"type":"q","text":"Are patient needs met consistently at all times including evenings and weekends?"},{"type":"q","text":"If a large number of patients are assigned to the same therapeutic activity, do patients have individualized goals within their treatment plans?"},{"type":"para","text":"(g)(2) Staffing Adequacy"},{"type":"p","text":"The number of qualified therapists, support personnel, and consultants must be adequate to provide comprehensive therapeutic activities consistent with each patient's active treatment program. Qualified staff must complete respective discipline assessments for use in multidisciplinary treatment planning. Established monitoring and evaluation mechanisms must be used to conduct consistent timely review of the quality and appropriateness of therapeutic and rehabilitative services."},{"type":"probe","text":"Probes §482.62(g)(2)"},{"type":"q","text":"Is there evidence that sampled patients and staff are familiar with the goals and staff interventions described in the patient's treatment plan? Are these observed interventions being carried out? What is the patient's response? Are these interventions and activities of sufficient frequency and intensity to achieve maximum therapeutic benefit?"},{"type":"q","text":"What are the qualifications, experience, duties, and responsibilities of the Therapeutic Activities Director and discipline supervisor(s)?"},{"type":"q","text":"Did the patients in the sample have a need for any therapeutic activities? Were their needs met?"},{"type":"q","text":"Did any of the patients in the sample indicate a need for therapeutic activities, but none were considered?"},{"type":"q","text":"What kinds of services are provided to the patient population?"},{"type":"q","text":"Why have therapeutic activities staff been deployed in the manner they have?"}]}];